`,ak=`---
title: Milestones
---

Track learner progress through your training by registering milestones - markers that fire when someone visits a page or clicks an element.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Progress signals, not surveillance
content:
Use milestones to understand where the training flow succeeds or breaks down. The useful question is whether the content supports completion, not whether an individual clicked everything.
\`\`\`

## Why milestones matter

Without progress data, you have no way to know whether learners finish your training or abandon it halfway through. Milestones give you that visibility. Each milestone is a signal - "this person reached this point" - that rolls up into completion and engagement metrics in the training admin. Think of milestones as checkpoints, not surveillance. The goal is to understand where learners get stuck so you can improve the content, not to monitor individuals.

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: Page visit
content: Fires automatically when a learner navigates to a specific page. No learner interaction required beyond opening the page. Use this for measuring reach - did people get to the conclusion? Did they open the optional deep-dive?
</1>
<2>
title: Button or link click
content: Fires when a learner clicks a specific element. Use this for measuring engagement - did they click the external resource link? Did they submit the reflection quiz?
</2>
\`\`\`

## Create milestones in the admin

Open your training in the admin panel at \`ai.joinhandshake.com/admin/trainings/TRAINING_ID\`. Each milestone you create there gets a unique ID. Copy that ID - you will need it when wiring milestones into your app.

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: Start simple
content:
The easiest completion signal is a single page-visit milestone on your last page. Add checkpoint milestones only when you need more granular progress data.
\`\`\`

## Wire milestones with the skill

Run \`/milestone\` in the Citadel agent. The skill walks you through three decisions:

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: Provide the milestone ID
content: Paste the ID from the training admin. The skill validates that it is not already registered in the manifest.
</1>
<2>
title: Choose the trigger type
content: Select **visit-page** for automatic page-load tracking, or **click** for element-interaction tracking.
</2>
<3>
title: Identify the target
content: For visit-page, name or describe the page ("the conclusion page" or \`/conclusion\`). For click, name or describe the element ("the Submit button on the quiz page" or the element's \`id\`). The skill resolves your description to the correct route or element, then wires the handler into the page component.
</3>
\`\`\`

## What the skill generates

Behind the scenes, the skill updates the manifest, validates routes and element IDs, and adds the tracking code to the correct page. First, it registers the milestone in the manifest frontmatter of \`src/content/manifest.md\`:

\`\`\`code-block
language: yaml
content:
milestones:
  - id: completed-training
    action: visit-page
    route: /conclusion
  - id: clicked-resource-link
    action: click
    buttonId: external-resource
\`\`\`

Second, it adds the tracking code to the target page component. For page visits, that is a single hook call:

\`\`\`code-block
language: tsx
content:
import { useMilestonePageView } from "@/hooks/useMilestone";

// Inside the component, before the return:
useMilestonePageView("completed-training");
\`\`\`

For clicks, it attaches a handler to the target element:

\`\`\`code-block
language: tsx
content:
import { trackClick } from "@/lib/milestones";

<Button id="external-resource" onClick={trackClick("clicked-resource-link")}>
  View resource
</Button>
\`\`\`

## Choosing a milestone strategy

How many milestones you register depends on what you need to learn about your learners.

\`\`\`accordion
<1>
title: Completion only
content: Register one visit-page milestone on your final page. If a learner reaches the last page, they completed the training. This is the simplest setup and covers the most common reporting need.
</1>
<2>
title: Checkpoint progress
content: Register visit-page milestones on several pages throughout the training - typically at the end of each major section. This tells you not just whether someone finished, but how far they got before dropping off. Three to five checkpoints across a ten-page training is usually enough.
</2>
<3>
title: Engagement depth
content: Add click milestones on key interactive elements: a quiz submission button, an external resource link, a reflection checklist. These measure whether learners are engaging with the content, not just scrolling past it. Use sparingly - tracking every click creates noise without insight.
</3>
\`\`\`

## Validation rules

The milestone system enforces several rules to prevent misconfiguration. The QA check verifies these before every commit:

\`\`\`checklist
<1>
id: unique-ids
label: Each milestone ID is unique across the manifest
</1>
<2>
id: valid-routes
label: Every visit-page route matches an existing page in the manifest navigation
</2>
<3>
id: single-button-id
label: Every click button ID appears as an element \`id\` exactly once in exactly one page
</3>
<4>
id: registered-handler
label: Every registered milestone has a corresponding handler in the page component code
</4>
<5>
id: no-orphans
label: No orphaned handlers remain after manifest changes
</5>
\`\`\`
