`,b3='---\ntitle: Overview of the task\n---\n\nAt a high level, authoring a task is a fork → branch → implement → push → PR loop against the upstream template repo. The commands below are the full shape of that loop - each step in this guide fills in the `... implement the task ...` middle.\n\n\n```code-block\nlanguage: bash\ncontent:\ngh repo fork handshake-project-dynamo/dynamo-<repo_id>-<domain> --clone\ncd dynamo-<repo_id>-<domain>/task\ngit checkout -b submission\n#  ... implement the task (see below) ...\ngit add -A && git commit -m "Task submission"\ngit push -u origin submission\ngh pr create --repo handshake-project-dynamo/dynamo-<repo_id>-<domain> --fill\n```\n\n## What each command does\n\n- **`gh repo fork ... --clone`** - forks the template repo to your GitHub account and clones your fork locally. You always work from a fork, never directly on the upstream repo.\n- **`cd dynamo-<repo_id>-<domain>/task`** - moves into the `task/` directory inside the freshly cloned repo so the rest of the commands run in the right place.\n- **`git checkout -b submission`** - creates a new branch named `submission` off the default branch. All your task work lives here; `main` stays clean.\n- **Implement the task** - this is the bulk of the work covered by the rest of this guide: scaffold the repo, write `solve.sh`, the tests, the Dockerfile, `instruction.md`, and `task.toml`, then calibrate locally.\n- **`git add -A && git commit ...`** - stages every file you touched and records the work as a commit on the `submission` branch.\n- **`git push -u origin submission`** - pushes the branch to your fork on GitHub and sets it as the upstream so future `git push` calls just work.\n- **`gh pr create --repo ... --fill`** - opens a pull request from your fork\'s `submission` branch into the upstream template repo, using your commit messages to fill the title and body.\n\n## Task walkthrough\n\n```embed\ntitle: Task walkthrough\nurl: https://www.loom.com/embed/c6b1830ba5cc4609b9db22ffaa84c3c7\n```\n\n',y3=`---
title: Common errors and examples
---

Four rejected tasks, one underlying mistake: **the verifier enforces a requirement the instruction never states.** Expand each card to see the problem, the code evidence, and how to avoid it.

\`\`\`\`accordion
allowMultiple: true
<1>
title: 1 · dvs1lya — sqlite-job-queue  ·  Undisclosed string literal
content:
<details>
<summary><strong>View code excerpts</strong></summary>

**instruction.md** — defers history-row format to the docstring

\`\`\`text
Keep the public \`SQLiteJobQueue\` class working with the methods and rules in the
file docstring. The exact lease TTL, retry delay, max attempt rules, history row
format, and reserve tie-break order are defined there.
\`\`\`

**environment/scheduler/queue.py** — the docstring it points to (lines 28–29)

\`\`\`text
Every real state change writes a history row.
History rows have job_id, event, worker_id, at, and details fields.

# The docstring lists the five fields but never specifies what the \`details\`
# dict must contain for ANY event (enqueued / reserved / completed / failed /
# expired / dead).
\`\`\`

**tests/test_outputs.py** — verifier asserts an exact details literal (lines 98–114)

\`\`\`python
def test_expired_final_attempt_goes_dead_on_reap_and_reserve():
    """An expired job at max attempts is dead and cannot be leased again."""
    ...
    assert q.snapshot()["final"]["state"] == "dead"
    assert q.history()[-1] == {
        "job_id": "final",
        "event": "dead",
        "worker_id": "worker-a",
        "at": 6,
        "details": {"reason": "lease_expired"},   # <-- exact literal, never disclosed
    }
\`\`\`

**solution/queue_fixed.py** — where the oracle invents the literal

\`\`\`python
# Oracle solution (solution/queue_fixed.py), the reap() -> "dead" transition:
self._history(row["job_id"], "dead", row["locked_by"], now, {"reason": "lease_expired"})

# grep across instruction.md and environment/ for "lease_expired" -> NOT FOUND.
# The agent has no source from which to derive the required reason string.
\`\`\`

</details>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-negative);background:var(--status-negative);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">Problem</div>
The verifier requires the dead-on-expiry history row to carry an exact literal — <code>details = {"reason":"lease_expired"}</code> — that appears nowhere in the instruction or the docstring it points to. The docstring lists the five history fields but never says what <code>details</code> should contain for any event, so the agent has no source to derive the string from.
</div>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-positive);background:var(--status-positive);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">How to avoid it</div>
Disclose the <code>details</code> schema in the docstring — the exact payload for each event, including the expiry-driven <code>dead</code> row. Or relax the verifier so it asserts only on the documented fields and ignores undocumented <code>details</code> contents.
</div>
</1>
<2>
title: 2 · uwlu38y — billing-ledger-repair  ·  Naming convention not specified
content:
<details>
<summary><strong>View code excerpts</strong></summary>

**instruction.md** — \`finding_id\` required but format never given (lines 30, 32)

\`\`\`text
# instruction.md, line 30 (global_findings):
...\`global_findings\` is sorted by \`finding_id\`; each object must contain exactly
\`finding_id\`, \`finding_code\`, \`severity\`, \`evidence_values\`, and \`required_values\`...

# instruction.md, line 32 (account_findings):
...Each object must contain exactly \`finding_id\`, \`account_id\`, \`legacy_balance_cents\`,
... \`finding_codes\`, and \`evidence_event_ids\`...

# \`finding_id\` is a REQUIRED field in both lists, but its format/scheme is never specified.
\`\`\`

**tests/test_outputs.py** — exact-equality bakes in F001–F007 (lines 289, 476–479)

\`\`\`python
EXPECTED_FINDINGS = {
    'generated_from': 'legacy_close_snapshot.json',
    'global_findings': [
        {'finding_id': 'F001', 'finding_code': 'entry_type_namespace_leak', ...},
    ],
    'account_findings': [
        {'finding_id': 'F002', 'account_id': 'acct_acorn',   ...},
        {'finding_id': 'F003', 'account_id': 'acct_bay',     ...},
        {'finding_id': 'F004', 'account_id': 'acct_cinder',  ...},
        {'finding_id': 'F005', 'account_id': 'acct_delta',   ...},
        {'finding_id': 'F006', 'account_id': 'acct_echo',    ...},
        {'finding_id': 'F007', 'account_id': 'acct_unknown', ...},
    ],
    'totals': {'global_finding_count': 1, 'account_finding_count': 6, ...},
}

def test_reconciliation_findings_are_exact():
    findings = load_findings()
    assert findings == EXPECTED_FINDINGS          # full exact-equality, incl. finding_id

# Hardcoded single sequential namespace: F001 (global) then F002-F007 (accounts).
\`\`\`

</details>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-negative);background:var(--status-negative);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">Problem</div>
<code>finding_id</code> is a required output field, but neither the instruction nor the success criteria define its format. The verifier hardcodes one sequential scheme — <code>F001</code> for the global finding, then <code>F002</code>–<code>F007</code> for the six account findings — and rejects any defensible two-namespace alternative.
</div>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-positive);background:var(--status-positive);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">How to avoid it</div>
Specify the <code>finding_id</code> scheme in the instruction — for example, sequential <code>F001</code>, <code>F002</code>, … across all findings, global first (sorted), then account (sorted by <code>account_id</code>). Or relax the verifier to match by <code>account_id</code> and <code>finding_code</code> instead of literal IDs.
</div>
</2>
<3>
title: 3 · w1y3uq4 — retrieval-audit  ·  Aggregation semantics not specified
content:
<details>
<summary><strong>View code excerpts</strong></summary>

**instruction.md** — four reasons listed; no priority order (lines 13–15, 35)

\`\`\`text
# instruction.md, lines 13-15 (validity condition):
A candidate is valid iff its \`tenant\`, \`language\`, \`embedding_model\`, and
\`snapshot_id\` match the canonical \`query_start\`...

# instruction.md, line 35 (output field):
- \`invalid_reason_histogram\`: reason -> count, where reasons are \`tenant\`,
  \`language\`, \`model\`, \`snapshot\`

# Never stated: that each invalid candidate is attributed to EXACTLY ONE reason,
# nor the priority order to use when a candidate fails more than one check.
\`\`\`

**tests/test_outputs.py** — histogram must sum to invalid_candidate_count (lines 71–75)

\`\`\`python
def test_invalid_candidate_breakdown():
    data = load_report()
    assert data["invalid_candidate_count"] == 313
    assert data["invalid_reason_histogram"] == {
        "language": 72, "model": 61, "snapshot": 61, "tenant": 119
    }

# 72 + 61 + 61 + 119 = 313 == invalid_candidate_count  ->  one reason per candidate.
# Agents that counted every failing reason produced a histogram summing to 373.
\`\`\`

**solution/solve.py** — the oracle's hidden priority cascade

\`\`\`python
# solution/solve.py -- the oracle assigns ONE reason via a fixed priority cascade:
def invalid_reason(candidate, start):
    if candidate["tenant"]          != start["tenant"]:          return "tenant"
    if candidate["language"]        != start["language"]:        return "language"
    if candidate["embedding_model"] != start["embedding_model"]: return "model"
    if candidate["snapshot_id"]     != start["snapshot_id"]:     return "snapshot"
    ...

# histogram incremented once per invalid candidate (first failing check wins):
reason = invalid_reason(candidate, start)
if reason:
    invalid_count += 1
    invalid_histogram[reason] += 1
\`\`\`

</details>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-negative);background:var(--status-negative);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">Problem</div>
A candidate can violate several constraints at once. The reference attributes each invalid candidate to exactly one reason via a hidden priority cascade <code>tenant → language → model → snapshot</code>, so the histogram sums to 313. The instruction lists the reasons but never states the single-assignment rule or the tie-break order — agents who counted every failing check produced 373 and were rejected.
</div>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-positive);background:var(--status-positive);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">How to avoid it</div>
State the rule explicitly: each invalid candidate is attributed to exactly one reason, evaluated in priority order <code>tenant → language → model → snapshot</code> (first failing check wins), so <code>sum(histogram) == invalid_candidate_count</code>. Or relax the verifier to accept independent multi-reason counting.
</div>
</3>
<4>
title: 4 · oqivawj — event-log-compaction  ·  Underspecified duplicate handling
content:
<details>
<summary><strong>View code excerpts</strong></summary>

**instruction.md** — duplicates never mentioned (lines 2–4)

\`\`\`text
The event sourcing engine at \`/app/engine.py\` maintains an integer counter
starting at 0. It processes a sequence of INCREMENT, DECREMENT, and SET events
from \`/app/events.jsonl\` and supports snapshot compaction to summarize history.

The engine contains bugs that cause incorrect counter values. Find and fix the
bugs in \`/app/engine.py\`. Do not modify \`/app/events.jsonl\` or \`/app/run.py\`.

# No mention of redelivered / duplicate-seq records, or how duplicates must be treated.
\`\`\`

**environment/data/engine.py** — starter code de-duplicates by seq

\`\`\`python
# environment/data/engine.py -- the starter code de-duplicates by seq:
def _load_events():
    seen_seqs = set()
    raw = []
    with open(EVENTS_PATH) as f:
        for line in f:
            line = line.strip()
            if line:
                e = json.loads(line)
                if e["seq"] not in seen_seqs:     # dedup-by-seq, keeps FIRST occurrence
                    seen_seqs.add(e["seq"])
                    raw.append(e)
    raw.sort(key=lambda e: e["seq"])
    return raw

# Redeliveries are placed BEFORE their originals and carry different values, so
# "keep first" keeps the wrong record. A dedup-by-seq guard is the textbook
# at-least-once pattern -- but the hidden reference removes dedup entirely.
\`\`\`

**tests/reference.py** — hidden ground truth applies every line

\`\`\`python
# tests/reference.py  (never shown to the agent) -- defines what "correct" means:
def compute_expected(events_path):
    """Full replay without compaction to get the correct final counter value."""
    state = 0
    with open(events_path) as f:
        for line in f:
            line = line.strip()
            if line:
                state = apply_event(state, json.loads(line))   # EVERY line, no dedup
    return state

# So the verifier's "correct" answer applies a duplicated seq twice. Whether that
# is the one sound event-sourcing semantics is exactly what the reviewer disputes.
\`\`\`

</details>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-negative);background:var(--status-negative);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">Problem</div>
The hidden reference applies every line of <code>events.jsonl</code> with no de-duplication, so duplicated <code>seq</code> values are applied twice. The instruction only says "find and fix the bugs" and never describes redelivery or duplicate handling — an engineer who keeps the textbook dedup-by-seq guard gets a different counter and fails.
</div>

<div style="border-left:3px solid var(--interactive-positive);background:var(--status-positive);padding:12px 14px;border-radius:6px;margin-top:12px;">
<div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.04em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fg-secondary);margin-bottom:4px;">How to avoid it</div>
Make duplicate / redelivery handling explicit — either "apply every line in <code>seq</code> order with no de-duplication" or define the canonical dedup rule the engine must implement and why. That removes the silent dependence on an unstated choice.
</div>
</4>
\`\`\`\`

## Before you submit: quick self-check

Tick each item once you've confirmed it for your task.

\`\`\`checklist
title: Quick self-check
<1>
id: spec-formats
label: Every output field's format and naming is fully specified — IDs, enums, and any exact string literals — so the agent never has to guess (e.g. \`finding_id\` format, the \`details\` \`reason\` string).
</1>
<2>
id: verifier-matches-instruction
label: The verifier only checks things the instruction (or a doc it points to) actually states — no hidden literals or undocumented fields.
</2>
<3>
id: canonical-rule
label: When a value can be computed more than one valid way, the instruction names the single canonical rule — single-assignment, priority / tie-break order, and sort order.
</3>
<4>
id: edge-cases
label: Duplicate, redelivery, and other edge cases are described explicitly — e.g. dedup by key, and how ties resolve.
</4>
<5>
id: alt-implementations
label: A reasonable alternative implementation still passes — the verifier isn't silently enforcing the oracle's arbitrary choice; if only one approach is valid, the instruction says so.
</5>
<6>
id: no-answer-leak
label: No file the agent can read (docstrings, comments, READMEs, filenames) discloses the bug, the fix, or the expected output.
</6>
<7>
id: no-misleading-content
label: No undisclosed file or detail steers the agent toward a non-golden answer — the task fails on the agent's own wrong call, not because the environment misled it. Every file the agent should use is named in the instruction.
</7>
<8>
id: no-injection
label: No malicious or destructive code, and no text in env files, comments, READMEs, or fixtures that tells the agent to ignore the task, reveal answers, or tamper with grading; no obfuscated or encoded payloads.
</8>
\`\`\`
`,ik=`---
title: Practice - is it gradable?
---

A success criterion is only useful if a test can check it. The grader never watches the agent work; it runs after the agent stops and inspects what's left on disk. So every criterion has to resolve to an artifact a test can open and a value it can assert on.

This is the real shape of \`tests/test_outputs.py\`. The task: deduplicate a CSV and write it to \`/app/output/clean.csv\`. You write the assertions - but a test that only passes on the correct file grades nothing. Yours is run against the golden output **and** four broken outputs an agent might plausibly produce. A sound test accepts the golden one and rejects every broken one. Anything less is a criterion the benchmark can't trust.

\`\`\`custom-tokens
assertion-runner: true
drill-prompt: Write assertions that accept the correctly deduplicated file and reject each broken variant below. The grader only trusts a criterion you can express here.
file-label: Golden output (what a correct solve.sh produces)
sample-file-path: /app/output/clean.csv
editor-label: Your test (Python)
fixtures-label: Your test is run against
expect-pass: must accept
expect-fail: must reject
got-pass: your test accepted it
got-fail: your test rejected it
outcome-correct: Handled
outcome-wrong: Missed
run-label: Run against all fixtures
loading-message: Loading Python…
reset-label: Reset
runtime-error-label: Runtime error
solution-label: The check that handles this case
success-message: Sound test - it accepts the golden output and rejects every broken one.
failure-message: Not sound yet - a sound test must accept the golden output and reject every broken one.
starter-code: import csv\\n\\nwith open("/app/output/clean.csv") as f:\\n    rows = list(csv.reader(f))\\n\\nheader, data = rows[0], rows[1:]\\n\\n# Write assertions that accept the golden output and reject every broken one.\\n# TODO
fixture-1-label: Golden - three unique rows
fixture-1-expect: pass
fixture-1-content: id,sku,qty\\n1,A100,5\\n2,B200,3\\n3,C300,8
fixture-1-solution: # The full reference test - every check a sound test needs.\\nheader, data = rows[0], rows[1:]\\nassert header == ["id", "sku", "qty"], f"unexpected header: {header}"\\nassert len(data) == 3, f"expected 3 rows, got {len(data)}"\\nassert len({r[0] for r in data}) == len(data), "duplicate ids remain"
fixture-2-label: Duplicates not removed
fixture-2-expect: fail
fixture-2-content: id,sku,qty\\n1,A100,5\\n2,B200,3\\n2,B200,3\\n3,C300,8
fixture-2-solution: # Reject leftover duplicates: ids must be unique and there must be exactly 3.\\nassert len(data) == 3, f"expected 3 rows, got {len(data)}"\\nassert len({r[0] for r in data}) == len(data), "duplicate ids remain"
fixture-3-label: Header renamed
fixture-3-expect: fail
fixture-3-content: id,sku,quantity\\n1,A100,5\\n2,B200,3\\n3,C300,8
fixture-3-solution: # Pin the exact header so a renamed column fails.\\nassert header == ["id", "sku", "qty"], f"unexpected header: {header}"
fixture-4-label: Empty (header only)
fixture-4-expect: fail
fixture-4-content: id,sku,qty
fixture-4-solution: # Require the expected number of data rows - an empty file has none.\\nassert len(data) == 3, f"expected 3 rows, got {len(data)}"
fixture-5-label: Rows dropped
fixture-5-expect: fail
fixture-5-content: id,sku,qty\\n1,A100,5\\n2,B200,3
fixture-5-solution: # The same row-count check rejects a truncated file.\\nassert len(data) == 3, f"expected 3 rows, got {len(data)}"
\`\`\`

If you can't write a check that separates the golden output from these near-misses, that's the signal to reshape the task - not to loosen the test.
`,v3=`---
title: Audit the requirements
---

You're the reviewer now. Each item below is something a task author actually put in a submission. Flag the ones that break a workflow requirement and leave the ones that are sound. The reason and the fix appear once you decide.

\`\`\`flag-and-fix
instruction: Flag each item that violates a task requirement. Leave the correct ones alone.
keyLesson: A sound task pins exact /app paths, states criteria a test can assert on, bakes pinned test deps into the single environment/Dockerfile (so the verifier reuses it), writes reward to /logs/verifier/, and contains NO personal info in task.toml.
flagLabel: Violates a requirement
okLabel: Looks correct
buttonOrder: flag-ok
<1>
id: vague-path
text: instruction.md says "Save the cleaned data to the output folder."
meta: instruction.md
isProblematic: true
reason: Paths must be exact and absolute. "The output folder" is ambiguous, so the agent and the test can't agree on where the artifact lives.
improved: Write the deduplicated rows to /app/output/clean.csv.
</1>
<2>
id: unobservable-criterion
text: Success criterion - "The result should be correct and well-formatted."
meta: instruction.md
isProblematic: true
reason: Not self-verifiable. Every criterion has to be expressible as a pytest assertion on an observable artifact, and "correct" and "well-formatted" can't be asserted.
improved: /app/output/clean.csv has the header id,sku,qty and exactly the unique input rows.
</2>
<3>
id: test-deps-in-image
text: Dockerfile line - RUN pip install pandas==2.2.2 pytest
meta: environment/Dockerfile
isProblematic: true
reason: Test deps must be pinned. In single verifier mode there is one image — pytest does belong in environment/Dockerfile (the verifier reuses it), but every version must be pinned exactly so the verify-time install is deterministic.
improved: RUN pip install pandas==2.2.2 pytest==8.4.1 pytest-json-ctrf==0.3.5
</3>
<4>
id: author-present
text: task.toml adds an \`author_name\` and \`email\` field.
meta: task.toml
isProblematic: true
reason: task.toml has no author field, and no personal information (names, emails) may go in it — identity is recorded outside the manifest.
improved: Remove the author/email lines — task.toml carries no identity fields.
</4>
<5>
id: shebang-ok
text: solve.sh opens with #!/bin/bash on line 1.
meta: solution/solve.sh
isProblematic: false
reason: Correct — the bash shebang comes first, which is what solve.sh needs.
</5>
<6>
id: reward-path-ok
text: test.sh writes the score with - echo 1 > /logs/verifier/reward.txt
meta: tests/test.sh
isProblematic: false
reason: Correct — reward.txt and ctrf.json go to /logs/verifier/.
</6>
\`\`\`

If you flagged everything, look again — two of these are exactly right. The skill isn't suspicion; it's knowing which requirement each item is measured against.
`,x3=`---
title: Practice
---

Two short drills to pressure-test your judgment before you spend hours building. Neither asks you to write a full task - each isolates a place authors most often go wrong.

- **Audit the requirements** - read items from a real submission and flag the ones that break a workflow rule. This is the reviewer's job, and the fastest way to internalize what the checklist is actually checking for.
- **Is it gradable?** - write a test against sample outputs and see whether it accepts the correct one and rejects the near-misses.

Start with the audit. It builds the eye you'll need before any of the writing matters.
`,sk=`---
title: Collecting form responses
---

Apps built on ^Citadel^ can include forms that save user responses directly to your project's data store. All you need to connect a form is a small config block - copy it from the admin tool and hand it to the agent. After that, you can reference the form by name in any future prompt.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: The config is the contract
content:
The agent reads \`key_schema\` from the config and renders one submitted value per key. Do not invent extra fields outside that schema unless the admin config changes first.
\`\`\`

## Getting your form config

Every form in the admin tool has a config block you can copy to your clipboard. It looks like this:

\`\`\`code-block
language: json
content:
{
  "form_registration_id": "reg_abc123",
  "key_schema": ["response", "confidence", "notes"]
}
\`\`\`

\`form_registration_id\` is the unique identifier for this form. \`key_schema\` is the list of fields it expects - one entry per input you want to collect.

Copy that block from the admin tool, then paste it into your prompt the first time you set up that form. The agent saves it to \`app-config.json\` - the same file that holds your project role settings - so you only need to provide it once.

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: The agent asks first, then remembers
content:
When you ask for a form, the agent will ask for your config before it does anything else. Once you paste it, the config is saved to app-config.json and reused automatically any time you reference that form by name in a future prompt.
\`\`\`

## Setting up a form for the first time

When a form hasn't been connected yet, paste its config alongside your description. The agent reads the \`key_schema\` to know what inputs to render and saves the config so you don't need to paste it again.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Create a form that collects a response, a confidence level, and optional notes. Use this config to connect it to our store:

{
  "form_registration_id": "reg_abc123",
  "key_schema": ["response", "confidence", "notes"]
}
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Add an annotation form with fields for a label and a justification. Save the data when the user clicks Submit. Here is the config:

{
  "form_registration_id": "reg_xyz789",
  "key_schema": ["label", "justification"]
}
\`\`\`

## Using a form that's already been set up

Once a form's config has been saved, you can reference it by name. No need to paste the config again.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
The Submit button on this page should save the form data using the annotation form.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Wire up the feedback form to the Submit button on this page.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Add a submit button that saves using the annotation form.
\`\`\`

## Confirmation and error feedback

Every form submission automatically shows a brief confirmation message when data is saved successfully. If something goes wrong, an error message appears instead. You don't need to ask for this - it's included by default. If you want different wording:

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
After the annotation form submits, show a message that says "Response recorded" instead of the default confirmation.
\`\`\`

## Preview behavior in ^Lovable^

In ^Lovable^ and development previews, form submissions don't send data to the real backend. Instead, the submitted values are printed to the browser console so you can verify the form is wired up correctly. You can test the full submit flow without affecting production data.
`,w3=`---
title: Mirrored assessments
---

A mirrored assessment lets your ^Citadel^ app be the front-end for a real joinera assessment form - a quiz, a game, a drag-and-drop activity, anything - while joinera stays in charge of validating the submission, grading it, enforcing attempt limits, and granting attributes when a learner passes.

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Coming soon
content:
Mirrored assessments depend on backend work in joinera and learn-apps that is not yet live in production. The Citadel-side tooling described here works today and you can build and preview a full assessment with local fixtures, but real submission and grading are not available yet. Build and preview now; ship once the backend lands.
\`\`\`

## What you are and aren't building

You are not rebuilding grading - you are reusing it. The contract between your app and joinera is not the UI; it is the **payload shape**. Your activity can be as creative as you like, as long as its output satisfies the generated parser. joinera handles autograding, attempt limits, and attribute grants exactly as it does for a form taken directly on its own site.

A mirror is a pinned copy of one published form version, held locally as a config file plus two generated files (a typed parser and the form's display copy). You never hand-write the generated files - a deterministic generator produces them, and a check verifies they were never edited by hand.

## Setting one up

### Get the config from joinera

In the joinera admin tool, open the form, pick a **published** version, and use the **Copy citadel config** item in its menu. That puts a JSON envelope on your clipboard - the form's identity, its data model, and its attempt and time limits.

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: The paved path
content:
If you are working inside a training, use "Create assessment form" from the training page. That creates the form and links it to the training in one step, so you skip the separate link action that is easy to forget.
\`\`\`

### Mirror the form

Paste the copied JSON into your prompt and ask the agent to mirror it. The agent saves the config and generates a typed parser and the form's display copy for you.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Mirror this assessment form. Here is the config:

{ "kind": "citadel-mirrored-form", "schemaVersion": 1, ... }
\`\`\`

### Build your activity

Build whatever interaction you want, then hand its output to the submit function the gate gives you. Wrap the whole thing in the mirrored-form gate, which renders every status, verdict, and grading screen by default - you build only the active activity and restyle the screens you care about.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
On this page, build a 5-question quiz for the mirrored screening form. Show the attempts remaining, and confirm before the learner uses their last attempt.
\`\`\`

### Preview every screen

Local and ^Lovable^ previews never reach the backend - that is by design. Everything runs on fixtures, so you can preview any screen on demand by adding a query parameter to the URL:

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
?mirrorMock=ready          the activity, ready to attempt
?mirrorMock=lastAttempt     pins attempts to 1 - preview the confirm dialog
?mirrorMock=passed          the "you passed" screen
?mirrorMock=failed          a failed attempt with attempts remaining
?mirrorMock=locked          no attempts remaining
?mirrorMock=grading         the grading spinner
?mirrorMock=reviewPending   awaiting a human grader
?mirrorMock=notAvailable    not connected or not open to this learner
\`\`\`

Walk every scenario before you call the activity done.

### Update to a new version

When joinera publishes a new version, re-copy the config and ask the agent to bump the form version. It regenerates the parser and copy and tells you which fields changed so you can adjust your activity where needed.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: The generated files stay honest
content:
A check re-runs the generator and fails if a generated file was hand-edited or has gone stale. If it ever flags a problem, re-run the generator - never edit the generated files by hand to make it pass.
\`\`\`
`,lk=`---
title: Submit to ^LLM^
---

Use \`submitToEval\` when a learner writes something and the app should return model-generated feedback, critique, or scoring. You usually do not need to ask the agent to write the wiring from scratch - describe the learner experience you want, and the eval-submission skill handles the implementation pattern.

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: Ask for the experience, not the plumbing
content:
The eval-submission skill handles the hook, config lookup, pending state, and backend polling. Your prompt should describe the learner interaction and the evaluator project, not the endpoint implementation.
\`\`\`

## When to ask for it

Ask for eval submission when the app needs to respond to free text: a reflection answer, a justification, a rubric explanation, or a short response that should receive coaching. Do not use it just to save a response; if the goal is persistence, use form submission instead.

\`\`\`example-pair
good: "Add a feedback step for this reflection. Use the answerFeedback eval and show the returned message below the learner answer."
bad: "Call \`/submitToEval\` with this system prompt, model, temperature, and polling loop."
context: The first prompt describes the product behavior the learner should experience. The second bypasses the skill and asks the browser to control settings that belong on the backend.
\`\`\`

## What to include in your prompt

A strong prompt gives the agent four things: the learner task, the question context, the eval name or config, and where the returned feedback should appear.

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: Name the Learner Task
content: Say what the learner will write and what question or prompt their answer responds to.
</1>
<2>
title: Name the Evaluator
content: Reference the saved eval name if it already exists, or paste the eval config from the admin tool if this is the first setup.
</2>
<3>
title: Describe the Returned Effect
content: Tell the agent where the evaluator response should appear: below the answer, in a feedback panel, as an unlock condition, or as the next step in the activity.
</3>
<4>
title: Let the Skill Wire It
content: The agent will store config in \`app-config.json\`, use \`submitToEval\`, disable controls while pending, and keep model settings server-side.
</4>
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: If the eval is not configured yet
content:
Paste the eval config once or name the eval and let the agent ask for the project key. After it is saved in \`app-config.json\`, future prompts can refer to the eval by name.
\`\`\`

## Prompt examples

For first-time setup, include the eval config so the agent can save it before wiring the interaction.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Add a written reflection activity. Ask the learner: "What evidence would you check before approving this response?"

When they click Get feedback, send their answer to the answerFeedback eval and show the evaluator's response below the input.

Use this eval config:
{
  "project": "answer-feedback-v1"
}
\`\`\`

Once the config exists, reference the eval by name.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
On the practice page, add an AI feedback step after the learner writes their justification.

Use the existing answerFeedback eval. The button should say "Get feedback" and the returned message should appear in a feedback panel under the answer.
\`\`\`

You can also shape the tone of the returned experience without specifying backend settings.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Create a short-answer practice item. The learner should explain why one annotation is stronger than another.

Submit the learner's answer to the rubricFeedback eval and show the response as coaching, not as a pass/fail grade.
\`\`\`

## Preview behavior

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Preview behavior
content:
In Lovable and local development, the app returns \`resources/mocks/eval-response.json\` instead of calling the live evaluator. Edit that mock response when you want a predictable preview.
\`\`\`
`,uk=`---
title: Using user data
---

Every app built on Citadel has access to the authenticated user's ^Handshake^ profile - their name, what they study, their account type, and the roles they hold on annotation projects. You can use that data to personalize content without writing any code yourself. Just describe what you want in plain language.

## Prompting for personalization

The examples below show how to ask ^Claude^ or ^Lovable^ to wire up profile-based conditions. The agent reads the profile data automatically and implements the logic - you only need to describe the condition you want.

### Greet the user by name

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Show a personalized greeting using the current user's name.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
The welcome page should say "Hello" followed by the user's first name.
\`\`\`

### Show different content by field of study

Describe what you want to show and which field it applies to. The agent understands abbreviations and common names - you don't need to match any exact value.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
If the user is a CS major, show a computer science training module.
If they study econ, show an economics track instead.
Otherwise, show the general fellow training page.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Show a biology-specific intro for users with a life sciences background.
Everyone else should see the standard onboarding.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Show a machine learning resource section only to users with an ML or AI background.
\`\`\`

The agent recognizes majors, subfields, abbreviations, and related terms - "CS", "comp sci", "computer science", "ML", "AI", "orgo", "pre-med", "econ", "neuro", and many more.

### Show content by broad domain

Use domain names when you want to group related fields together rather than target a specific subfield.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Show a quantitative methods callout for users in engineering or math.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
If the user has a business background, surface the finance and accounting modules first.
\`\`\`

### Gate content by account type

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
This section should only be visible to internal Handshake users.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Show an "internal preview" banner to Handshake employees.
\`\`\`

### Gate content by email domain

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Only show the university resource hub to users with a .edu email address.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
If the user has a handshake.com email, show the employee note at the top of the page.
\`\`\`

### Gate content by project role

When asking for role-based conditions, either name the project or expect the agent to ask you for a project ID. The agent will save it to \`app-config.json\` so you only have to provide it once per app.

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
Only show the review queue to users who are Reviewers in this project.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
If the user is an annotator, show the annotation guide.
If they are a reviewer, show the quality checklist instead.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: The agent asks once, then remembers
content:
The first time you add a role-based condition, the agent will ask for your HAI annotation project ID if it hasn't been set. After you provide it, it's saved to app-config.json and used automatically for all future role checks in this app.
\`\`\`

---

## Advanced usage

The following sections explain the underlying implementation for developers who want to write or customize profile-based logic directly.

### Getting the current user

Import and call \`useCurrentUserProfile\` in any component. The hook returns a \`profile\` object once loaded, or \`undefined\` while the request is in flight.

\`\`\`code-block
language: typescript
content:
import { useCurrentUserProfile } from "@/hooks/useCurrentUserProfile";

function MyComponent() {
  const { data: profile, isLoading } = useCurrentUserProfile();

  if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (!profile) return null;

  return <p>Hello, {profile.fullName}</p>;
}
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Always guard on isLoading
content:
Never render profile-dependent UI before isLoading resolves. In Lovable the hook returns fixture data immediately; in production it awaits an API call. Skipping the guard produces flash-of-wrong-content bugs that only appear after deployment.
\`\`\`

In development and in ^Lovable^, the hook reads from \`resources/mocks/current-user-profile.json\` - no network calls. In production (\`VITE_APP_ENV=production\`), it fetches from \`/currentUserProfile\` with cookie auth.

### What the profile contains

| Field | Type | Notes |
|-------|------|-------|
| \`fullName\` | \`string\` | Display name - use for greetings |
| \`email\` | \`string\` | Primary email address |
| \`status\` | \`string\` | \`"ACTIVE"\` or \`"INTERNAL"\` (^Handshake^ employees) |
| \`attributes\` | \`ProfileAttribute[]\` | Academic fields, majors, and expertise areas |
| \`projectRoles\` | \`ProjectRole[]\` | Roles in ^HAI^ annotation projects |
| \`countryCode\` / \`stateCode\` | \`string\` | ISO location codes |
| \`handshakeUserId\` | \`number\` | ^Handshake^ platform user ID |
| \`currentOnboardingStage\` | \`string\` | Onboarding progress stage |

TypeScript types for all fields are exported from \`src/lib/resource-manifest.ts\`.

### Expertise and domain helpers

Import from \`src/lib/userProfileHelpers.ts\` - do not re-implement matching logic inline.

\`hasDomain\` checks top-level areas. \`hasExpertiseOrMajor\` checks both top-level areas and specific subfields. Both accept abbreviations and aliases.

\`\`\`code-block
language: typescript
content:
import { hasDomain, hasExpertiseOrMajor } from "@/lib/userProfileHelpers";

// Multi-branch routing with fallback:
const track = hasExpertiseOrMajor(profile, "CS")
  ? "cs"
  : hasExpertiseOrMajor(profile, "econ")
  ? "econ"
  : "general";
\`\`\`

### Account type and email helpers

\`\`\`code-block
language: typescript
content:
import { isInternalUser, hasEmailDomain } from "@/lib/userProfileHelpers";

{isInternalUser(profile) && <InternalPreviewBanner />}
{hasEmailDomain(profile, "university.edu") && <StudentResourceLink />}
\`\`\`

### Project role helper

\`hasProjectRole\` requires a \`projectId\`. Read it from \`app-config.json\` at the project root.

\`\`\`code-block
language: typescript
content:
import { hasProjectRole } from "@/lib/userProfileHelpers";
import appConfig from "../../app-config.json";

const projectId = appConfig.defaultProjectId;

{hasProjectRole(profile, "reviewer", projectId) && <ReviewerQueue />}
\`\`\`

The role name accepts aliases: \`"annotator"\` / \`"labeler"\`, \`"reviewer"\` / \`"validator"\`, \`"admin"\` / \`"administrator"\`, \`"fellow"\` / \`"fellows"\` / \`"fellowship"\`, \`"qa"\` / \`"quality analyst"\`.

Role names in HAI projects are often compound strings such as \`"Project Acme Fellow - Good"\`. Querying \`"fellow"\` (or any of its synonyms) matches any role whose name contains the word "fellow", so you don't need to spell out the full role name.

### Customizing the fixture

Edit \`resources/mocks/current-user-profile.json\` to simulate any user during local development. Swap \`status\`, change \`attributes\` values, or update \`projectRoles\` to test any branch of your conditional logic without touching the API.
`,ck=`---
title: Resources
---

The resource system lets Citadel apps fetch and display external data from APIs. Resources automatically switch between fixture data in development and real API endpoints in production.

## How it works

Resources follow a three-step pattern: define fixture data for local development, register the resource in a manifest, and fetch it in your component using a hook.

\`\`\`code-block
language: typescript
content:
// 1. Create fixture data: resources/mocks/my-data.json
{ "id": 1, "title": "Example item" }

// 2. Register in src/lib/resource-manifest.ts
import myDataMock from "../../resources/mocks/my-data.json";

export const RESOURCES = {
  myData: {
    key: "myData",
    apiUrl: "/myEndpoint",
    mockData: myDataMock,
  },
};

// 3. Fetch in a component
const { data, isLoading } = useResource<MyType>("myData");
\`\`\`

In Lovable and local development, the hook returns your fixture data directly with no network calls. In production, it fetches from the configured API URL with cookie authentication. This means you can build and test your UI without a live backend.

## Current user profile

The \`currentUserProfile\` resource provides access to the authenticated user's Handshake profile. It uses \`credentials: 'include'\` so that learn-apps cookies are forwarded automatically - the same auth pattern used by the milestone system. The API returns the profile wrapped in a \`"profile"\` key; the resource's \`transform\` unwraps this automatically so the hook returns a flat \`UserProfile\` object.

\`\`\`code-block
language: typescript
content:
import { useCurrentUserProfile } from "@/hooks/useCurrentUserProfile";

function MyComponent() {
  const { data: profile, isLoading, error } = useCurrentUserProfile();

  if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (!profile) return null;

  return <p>Welcome, {profile.fullName}</p>;
}
\`\`\`

The hook logs the profile to the browser console via \`console.table\` by default, so you can inspect the data shape during development.

## Fixture data

The fixture file at \`resources/mocks/current-user-profile.json\` ships with the template so that new projects have working data out of the box. It mirrors the real API envelope with the \`"profile"\` wrapper. You can customize the inner fields to match your testing needs.

\`\`\`code-block
language: json
content:
{
  "profile": {
    "id": "prof-local-1",
    "name": "jdoe",
    "fullName": "Jane Doe",
    "lastName": "Doe",
    "email": "jane.doe@example.com",
    "handshakeUserId": 12345,
    "currentOnboardingStage": "FULLY_ONBOARDED",
    "countryCode": "US",
    "stateCode": "CA",
    "profileAttributes": { "role": "fellow" },
    "status": "ACTIVE",
    "attributes": [
      {
        "id": "attr-1",
        "attribute": {
          "value": "engineering",
          "metadata": { "source": "manual" }
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: Inspect it in the console
content:
In development and Lovable, \`useCurrentUserProfile\` logs the full profile object to the browser console via \`console.table\` when data loads. Open DevTools to inspect the shape of the data and verify your fixture matches what you expect.
\`\`\`
`,k3=`---
title: Reviewer guide
---

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Project Dynamo — reviewer guide
content:
This guide is for **reviewers** on Project Dynamo. You already know how to build a strong Terminal-Bench task. This guide teaches the other side of the table: reaching the correct verdict (**Accept, Revise, or Reject**) on each task submission, with feedback the attempter can act on. Every task is reviewed twice on the platform before it moves to Pending Pass@. Review 2 is a second pass over Review 1's call.
\`\`\`

## 1. Your role: from building tasks to judging them

As a reviewer you look at a real Terminal-Bench task a fellow built and decide whether it can go forward. You assess the **whole task**, meaning the proposal and the task repo. Every review ends in one verdict (Accept, Revise, or Reject), plus a **1–5 Standard Quality Score**, **issue checkboxes**, a **comment**, and (in Review 1) a **Task Verdict** and **Fellow Verdict**.

Two things change from your work as an attempter.

You do **not** build, run, or execute anything; the automated layers below already did that. Your review is entirely **reading and judgment**: the subjective quality calls a machine can't reliably make. They span the whole task: whether it's hard enough, whether it's realistic, whether the pieces gel together, whether the verifier is robust, whether it's genuinely solvable.

And you judge the task as a **domain expert** would. Is it genuinely hard, fair, and correct? The task being hard for *you* is fine. You are judging the task's design, not your own ability to solve it.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: The mindset
content:
A task can pass every automated check and still be a bad task: incoherent across its files, too easy under the surface, ambiguous to a real practitioner, gradable by luck, or solvable by a trick. You are the layer that catches that, by **reading** the proposal and repo rather than running anything. These calls carry equal weight.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Your job is the judgment automation can't be trusted on
content:
Static checks can't see it, and an LLM grades it unreliably. Read the task as the **domain expert who would be paid to do this work** and judge:
- Do all the pieces gel together, with instruction, solution, tests, and environment all serving the *same* task?
- Is the task genuinely solvable as packaged, and does the solution actually solve the *stated* problem (not a narrower one)?
- Is it *genuinely* hard for an expert, or just hard-looking, tedious, or high-volume?
- Is the scenario realistic, and is the problem novel for this domain?
- Could a *sound* alternative expert method fail the verifier (ambiguity)?
- Is the verifier robust, with tolerances calibrated, no domain-specific shortcut or reward hack, and no answer the agent was never given (hidden knowledge)?
- Do the tests grade exactly what the instruction states, no more and no less?
- Does the solution genuinely compute the answer, or echo/hardcode it?

Each of these is covered one by one in [The judgment areas](/reviewing/judgment#4-the-judgment-areas).
\`\`\`

## 2. What the machine already did — and how far to trust it

By the time a task reaches you, several layers have already run. They fall into two groups.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Ignore entirely — handled internally, not your review scope
content:
- **Duplicate check against Terminal-Bench**: confirms the task isn't a near-duplicate of a prior submission. This isn't something a human can feasibly re-verify at this submission volume, and if it misses something, tuning it is on the Dynamo team.
- **Task validation results**: the platform builds the Docker image, runs the oracle (the task's own solution script) against the tests (all should pass), and runs a no-op test without the solution (which should fail). This mechanically exercises solvability and basic verifier strength. Assumed to be working as intended, so don't re-verify it.
- **Proposal gate**: the proposal already passed an automated LLM rubric check for specificity and difficulty.
- **Pass@2 at 900s**: an upstream cost gate only. These two runs decide whether the more expensive pass@5 is worth running; they are not part of your review. Every task that reaches you already has a pass@5, which carries far more signal about what the agents are doing, so judge the task on that. Disregard the pass@2 result even when it failed — a task that missed pass@2 but sits in the 0–2/5 pass@5 band is fine and should not be sent back on that basis.
- **Pass@5 at the author's chosen timeout**: five runs. The task was blocked only if the failures were **invalid** (timeouts or agent/verifier errors). A clean 0/5 with valid failures passes through as the hardest case.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: Read, but verify — an LLM first pass over the same criteria you judge
content:
- **Static checks on the PR**: LLM-based validations of file structure and content quality: coherence, difficulty, realism, novelty, solvability, ambiguity, verifiability, docstrings, cheat-resistance, solution quality, plus mechanical items (absolute paths, dependency pinning, Dockerfile hygiene, declared output files).
- **LLM rubric eval on the PR**: an automated pass over the full task rubric. Note: in the review tool this and the static checks often surface together as one combined checks panel, so you're not missing a second layer if you only see one section.

These two are fallible LLM judgments about exactly the things your review exists to judge. **Always read their notes section**, which flags likely issues worth a deeper look, but treat green as a hint rather than a verdict: your own read of the files overrides theirs in both directions.
\`\`\`

Format, packaging, obvious path/dependency errors, and "does the oracle pass" are largely covered by these layers. What is *not* pre-filtered for you is whether the pass@5 failures are actually **valid** failures. That's still your call ([The core skill: valid vs. invalid failures](/reviewing/judgment#5-the-core-skill-valid-vs-invalid-failures)).

## 3. Before you judge

\`\`\`checklist
<1>
id: read
label: Read the approved proposal and the fellow's task notes. Open the full task repo: instruction.md, task.toml (difficulty / solution / verification explanations), environment/, solution/, tests/, Dockerfile.
</1>
<2>
id: hash
label: Note the exact latest commit hash on the PR. You'll record it in HAI and review that commit (see [Recording your review in HAI](/reviewing/recording)).
</2>
<3>
id: history
label: Skim the PR's commit history for signs of manufactured difficulty, e.g. a clarifying instruction removed so that passing trials would start failing (see the [Decision rule](/reviewing/judgment#6-the-verdict-accept-revise-reject)).
</3>
<4>
id: feedback
label: Check for previous reviewer feedback. If the task was reviewed before, first confirm the fellow implemented the required changes.
</4>
<5>
id: passat
label: Open the pass@5 analysis — it's posted as a comment on the PR (click "Pass@ Analysis," or copy the comment's markdown) — and note the recorded score.
</5>
<6>
id: notes
label: Read the static-check notes for anything they flag.
</6>
\`\`\`

Walkthrough: Review of one example task end-to-end, covering the same flow this guide lays out.

\`\`\`embed
url: https://www.loom.com/embed/9fc32285058440d08176f59fee6a49fb
title: Reviewer walkthrough
\`\`\`

Then work through the judgment areas below, reading as a domain practitioner. Afterwards, record your verdict, 1–5 score, and feedback in HAI ([Recording your review in HAI](/reviewing/recording)).


**Related:** [The judgment areas](/reviewing/judgment) · [Scoring: checkboxes and the 1–5 score](/reviewing/scoring) · [Recording your review in HAI](/reviewing/recording)
`,E3=`---
title: Judgment areas, valid failures, and the verdict
---

## 4. The judgment areas

You are the domain expert for this task, so evaluate each area below with the same rigor you'd apply to this work professionally. Record what you find using the issue checkboxes and quality score ([Scoring](/reviewing/scoring)).

### The task as a whole

| **Judgment call** | **How to test it** | **If it fails → checkbox** |
|----|----|----|
| **Everything gels together** | Do \`instruction.md\`, \`solution/solve.sh\`, \`tests/\`, and the Dockerfile all describe and serve the *same* task? Does the environment provide what the solution needs; does \`solve.sh\` produce exactly the artifacts the tests read; do the tests check what the instruction asks for? A task where the pieces drift apart is broken even if each file looks fine alone. | **Instruction contain incorrect or irrelevant info** / **underspecified** as fits + comment |
| **Genuinely solvable** | From the instruction and the solution, does a real solution path exist, and does \`solve.sh\` actually solve the *stated* problem, not a narrower or different one? (The author's oracle passed; your job is to confirm it passes by solving the real task, not by sidestepping it.) | **Other** + comment: "not genuinely solvable / solves a narrower task." |

### Difficulty & realism

| **Judgment call** | **How to test it** | **If it fails → checkbox** |
|----|----|----|
| **Genuinely hard for an expert** | Would a competent domain expert (or an average undergrad in a few days) crack it quickly? Is the difficulty real reasoning, system design, or methodological judgment, or just tedium, volume, or obscure recall? | **Other** + comment: "too easy / difficulty is busywork." |
| **Not a kitchen-sink task** | Does the difficulty come from piling on dozens of interacting rules until the model slips on one of them? That failure is technically "valid" but the difficulty is artificial, and how the rules interact with the data is near-impossible to audit. | **Other** + comment: "difficulty is rule-overload, not reasoning." |
| **Realistic** | Would a real practitioner be paid to produce these outputs? Is the scenario authentic, and are the requested outputs what that person would actually want, not an artifact no one uses? | **Task is not realistic issue** |
| **Novel** | In this domain, is it a textbook or well-known published problem with a widely available solution a model could reproduce from memory? | **Other** + comment: "not novel / known solution." |

### The instruction

| **Judgment call** | **How to test it** | **If it fails → checkbox** |
|----|----|----|
| **Not over-directed** | Does the instruction hand over the method, mandate a specific tool/library, or walk through steps, removing the actual challenge? Grading should be on *what* is produced, not *how*. | **Instructions are overspecified** |
| **Unambiguous (sound-alternative test)** | Can you name a *specific sound* expert approach (a single coherent method a competent practitioner would choose, not an error or hybrid) that would FAIL verification? If yes, it's ambiguous/underspecified. Also: are arbitrary or non-standard choices the agent must match actually disclosed? | **Instructions are underspecified** |
| **No hidden knowledge** | Does the golden solution rely on a constant, schema, threshold, or fact that the agent was never given in the instruction or its inputs? The agent can only use what it can see. | **Instructions are underspecified** (or **incorrect/irrelevant info** if the disclosed info is wrong) + comment |
| **No incorrect or irrelevant info** | Are there wrong paths, contradictions, claims that don't match the repo, or leftover filler that could mislead the agent? | **Instruction contain incorrect or irrelevant info** |
| **No answer leakage** | Open the files the agent can read (docstrings, comments, READMEs). Does any disclose the bug, the fix, or the expected output? | **Other** + comment: "answer leaked in [file]; move reasoning to solution/tests." |
| **No misleading content** | Is there a file/detail, not referenced in the instruction, that points away from the golden answer? Would a reasonable agent follow it and fail for that? | **Instruction contain incorrect or irrelevant info** + comment. |

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Omission is not automatically ambiguity
content:
The instruction is not supposed to hand-hold; the agent should make its own choices of method and approach. An omitted detail is fine when a domain expert could **deduce** it from the instruction, the input files, or standard domain knowledge. The best tasks contain an apparent decision with a hidden requirement that the provided information is enough to resolve. It only becomes underspecification when the missing detail is an arbitrary or non-standard choice the agent must match and has no way to deduce.
\`\`\`

### The verifier

| **Judgment call** | **How to test it** | **If it fails → checkbox** |
|----|----|----|
| **Tolerances not too tight** | For each numeric band, would a genuinely correct solution produced by a *different sound method* still fall inside it? A band only the reference implementation can hit is too tight. | **Verifiers too tight. Low tolerances fail the tasks unfairly** |
| **Tolerances not too loose** | Would a plausible *wrong* method also land inside the band? Could a wrong-but-close answer pass? | **Verifiers too loose. Wrong answers pass through** |
| **No domain-specific cheat path** | Beyond generic anti-cheat: is there a shortcut a clever agent could exploit in THIS domain, such as an analytical shortcut the task means to exclude, an online lookup of the answer, exploiting a fixture, or hardcoding a value that happens to pass? | **Verifiers too loose** + comment |
| **Tests match the instruction 1:1** | Does every assertion trace to a requirement the instruction states (or clearly implies), and is every stated requirement actually tested? Grading on unstated criteria is an unfair stump; missing coverage lets wrong work pass. One trivially-minor requirement (of many) left untested is non-blocking, so score it 4. Material coverage gaps are a Revise. | **underspecified** / **overspecified** / **incorrect info** as fits + comment |
| **No injection or malicious content** | Scan env files, comments, READMEs, and fixtures for text that tells the agent to ignore the task / reveal answers / tamper with grading, and for obfuscated or encoded payloads. | **Other** + comment. |
| **Deterministic** | Are seeds/inputs fixed and ordering stable, with nothing depending on wall-clock/date or live-generated data? | **Other** + comment: "nondeterministic, fix seeds/inputs." |
| **Requirements traceable** | Can you trace each material instruction requirement to a solution step and a verifier assertion (and back)? | **Other** + comment. |

### The solution

| **Judgment call** | **How to test it** | **If it fails → checkbox** |
|----|----|----|
| **Solution genuinely solves it** | Does \`solve.sh\` actually compute the answer through real work, or does it echo/hardcode a precomputed result? Are expected values in tests/ derived, not pasted in? | **Other** + comment: "solution doesn't genuinely compute / hardcoded." |

### Metadata labels

The \`task.toml\` \`[metadata]\` block tags the task with controlled-vocabulary labels from \`.dynamo/diversity-taxonomy.toml\` (browseable on the [Task categories](/task-categories) page). **Only \`task_objective\` and \`artifact_type\` are the fellow's job**. \`category\` and \`subcategory\` are seeded by the Dynamo team in the platform task and must be left untouched. Your check is that the task the PR implements still matches them. Both fellow-set fields must be filled with the **best available fit** (lowercase \`snake_case\` labels from the taxonomy), not a loose match and never an empty array. These labels drive dataset-level diversity tracking, so a wrong or missing label silently corrupts the benchmark mix.

| **Judgment call** | **How to test it** | **If it fails → checkbox** |
|----|----|----|
| **No placeholder defaults** | Neither \`task_objective\` nor \`artifact_type\` is empty or still holds scaffold text. | **Metadata labels missing, placeholder, or wrong fit** + comment |
| **\`category\` / \`subcategory\` still match the PR** | These were seeded by the Dynamo team in the platform task. Confirm the fellow hasn't changed them **and** that the task the PR actually implements still fits them, since attempters often edit the PR until it passes and forget the platform entry drifted. If a mismatch is the only issue, **Accept at a 3**: the task is deliverable, and the 3 logs that the platform category needs correcting (see the [Decision rule](#6-the-verdict-accept-revise-reject)). | **Metadata labels missing, placeholder, or wrong fit** |
| **\`task_objective\`: valid array, best fit** | A non-empty array where every entry is a lowercase \`snake_case\` label from \`.dynamo/diversity-taxonomy.toml\` and reflects the task's **end goal**, not the tools, files, or commands used to get there. Multiple labels are allowed when several genuinely apply. | **Metadata labels missing, placeholder, or wrong fit** |
| **\`artifact_type\`: valid array, best fit** | A non-empty array where every entry is a lowercase \`snake_case\` label from \`.dynamo/diversity-taxonomy.toml\` and names the **central** objects the task operates on, not incidental helper scripts, logs, or temporary outputs. Multiple labels are allowed when several genuinely apply. | **Metadata labels missing, placeholder, or wrong fit** |

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Best fit, not just valid
content:
A label can be spelled correctly and still be wrong. Read the task, decide what it is really about, and confirm the fellow picked the closest label(s). A \`debug\` task tagged \`implement\`, or a database task tagged only \`text_or_log_file\`, is a wrong-fit failure even though the labels exist in the vocabulary. If a value sits outside the controlled vocabulary in \`.dynamo/diversity-taxonomy.toml\` entirely, it's also a fail.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: When in doubt, write it down
content:
If you suspect an issue but can't fully confirm it (e.g. a tolerance you think is too tight but can't recompute), select the closest checkbox and say so in the comment with your reasoning. A flagged uncertainty is far more useful to the next reviewer and the author than a silent pass.
\`\`\`

## 5. The core skill: valid vs. invalid failures

As an attempter you experienced the pass@ gates from the other side. As a reviewer, reading them is a judgment call, and it is the one part of the pipeline **not** pre-filtered for you. A good task is a **solvable stump**: the oracle solves it (proving it's solvable) while the model fails at least 3 of 5 (proving it's hard), and a clean 0/5 of valid failures is the hardest case. The failures must be the model getting the answer **wrong**, never running out of time. A timeout is not a valid failure.

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: The proof standard for a valid failure
content:
A failure is **valid** only if you can point to something concrete, such as a sentence in the instruction or an analysis of the input files, that *proves* the agent's approach or decision was incorrect. If instead an expert could defend the approach from the instruction alone ("nothing here forbids this; given what was provided, this is a reasonable method"), the task is ambiguous and the failure is **invalid**, even if the trial-analysis panel calls it valid.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Reading the trial analysis panel
content:
Each trial's analysis breaks into: a Per-Trajectory Rubric (task specification, reward hacking, difficulty crux, near miss, refusal, timeout, approach validity), Fail Reasons, Golden vs. Agent Values, Failing Tests, Golden Solution Approach, Agent Approach, the difference between the two, a Validity-of-Agent-Approach call, a Rubric Aggregate, and a final Summary. Treat all of it as an LLM first pass rather than ground truth. It can be wrong in either direction, and it can be fooled by an incorrect \`task.toml\` difficulty explanation. (If the difficulty explanation itself states a wrong "correct" answer, the panel may score a genuinely correct agent trial as a valid failure, so check the difficulty explanation against your own read of the solution when something looks off.) If the panel isn't enough, use View Logs and Artifacts to pull the full agent trajectory, which is expected to be rare rather than routine.

The full path: View logs & artifacts → "trials" in the left panel → expand "Upload Harbor Output" for the download link.

One fast diagnostic: if the failing tests are about file existence or output formatting, treat it as a red flag rather than real difficulty — it usually means a naming/format convention the instruction never disclosed, which is an ambiguity (invalid failure), not a genuine stump.
\`\`\`

| **Judgment call** | **How to test it** | **If it fails → action** |
|----|----|----|
| **Pass@5 in the target band** | Is the score in the **0–2/5** band (pass@5 ≤ 2/5) with **valid** failures? A clean **0/5** (all valid fails, oracle solves it) is the hardest case and is good; **3–5/5** = too easy. A task in this band is fine regardless of its pass@2 result. Note which agent/model ran the trials, since it can vary by task. | **0/5 with invalid failures** (timeout / agent / verifier) → send back to fix the cause. **3–5/5** → send back with guidance to raise *real* difficulty (edge cases, multi-step reasoning, stronger verifier), not lower the timeout or add busywork. |
| **Failures are legitimate, not timeouts** | Open the job analysis: are the failing runs producing *wrong answers*, or just hitting the time limit? | If failures are timeouts, the difficulty is fake. Send back to move difficulty into reasoning, not compute time. |
| **Failures aren't prompt ambiguity** | Are the runs failing because the prompt admits more than one reasonable interpretation, rather than because the problem is genuinely hard? | **Instructions are underspecified** + comment. |
| **Agent consensus vs. golden** | If most or all failing trials converge on the same value/approach that differs from golden, don't default to "the agents are wrong." Check whether the golden solution is actually correct, whether an undisclosed rule is making agents fail unfairly, or whether the agents found a legitimate approach the golden solution disregards. | **Instructions are underspecified**, or **Other** (if golden itself is wrong) + comment. |
| **Verifier tests the real requirement** | Does the verifier check what the task actually asks, and is it robust rather than brittle (it accepts any sound correct answer, rejects wrong ones)? | **Verifiers too tight** / **too loose** as fits + comment. |
| **Timeout justified and ≤ 900s** | Did the author justify their chosen timeout, and is it within the 900s hard cap and long enough for the model to produce an answer? | **Other** + comment: "timeout unjustified / exceeds cap / too short to finish." |
| **Trace reviewed for cheating** | Skim a representative agent trace: did it do the work, or shortcut / read ground truth / tamper with the verifier? | **Other** + comment. |

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Send back to attempt when…
content:
Two pass@5 outcomes always go back to the fellow, regardless of how good the rest of the task looks:
- **0/5 from invalid failures** (timeout, ambiguity, brittle verifier): send back to fix the cause; a clean 0/5 with valid failures and a passing oracle is fine.
- **3–5/5 on pass@5** (pass@5 > 2/5): too easy; tell the fellow to raise the difficulty of getting it *right*, never to lower the timeout or add busywork.

See [Understanding Pass@ & Timeouts](/submit/pass-at) for the full fellow-facing policy.
\`\`\`

## 6. The verdict: Accept / Revise / Reject

Everything you've found now collapses into one call.

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: Accept
content:
Accept if the PR has no issues. A mismatch between the proposal and the platform's task description is fine on its own, since that's just metadata and can be corrected after the fact. This holds even for a **category/subcategory mismatch**: if the task the PR implements is clean but belongs to a different category than the platform records, Accept the task and score it a 3 to log the mismatch (rather than 4 or 5). The task is deliverable; the 3 flags that the platform's category needs correcting so the task-type distribution the project requires isn't silently eroded (\`category\`/\`subcategory\` are seeded in the platform by the Dynamo team; see the Metadata labels subsection in [§4 The judgment areas](#4-the-judgment-areas)).
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Revise
content:
Revise in every other case: a real but fixable problem that does not collapse the task's difficulty. Send it back with actionable feedback.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: Reject
content:
Reject if the task's difficulty is illegitimate or the task is unsalvageable, meaning fixing the problem would make the task easy or it needs a rebuild from scratch. Reject when any hold:
- Most models failed because of an undisclosed requirement enforced in the verifier.
- Trials failed because the model misunderstood an ambiguous term, and clarifying it would lead to a perfect answer.
- The agents solved every aspect correctly but failed on a choice that is still valid and was never pinned by the instruction (ordering, naming, or formatting conventions not specified or unclear); pinning it would lead to a correct answer.
- The instruction or input data contains red herrings that deliberately lead the agent to an incorrect answer.
- The difficulty was manufactured: e.g. the commit history shows a clarifying instruction was removed so a passing task would start failing, and fixing the ambiguity makes the task solvable, so the difficulty was never real.
- Trials failed because the instruction or input files contain incorrect information that was never disclosed (the model had no reason to distrust the given information).
- All agent failures were caused by an overly strict verifier that rejected valid answers.
- There are other critical issues that would require starting from scratch, not just fixing.
- The attempter ignored feedback from a previous reviewer and did not implement the required fixes (or disputed the feedback without addressing it).
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: The hardest call — Reject vs Revise
content:
Both send the task back, but they differ. When the failure comes from something missing or wrong in the task, ask: *if I fix it, is the task still genuinely hard?* If yes → Revise (tell the fellow exactly what to change). If fixing it makes the task easy or trivial → Reject (the difficulty was never legitimate).
\`\`\`

**Related:** [Reviewer guide](/reviewing) · [Scoring: checkboxes and the 1–5 score](/reviewing/scoring) · [Recording your review in HAI](/reviewing/recording)
`,T3=`---
title: Recording your review in HAI
---

## 8. Recording your review in HAI

After you've judged the task and chosen a score and issue flags, you record your review in HAI. The Review-1 form has these fields. Fill them in this order.

### 8.1 R1 Reviewed PR Commit Hash

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: Record the exact commit you reviewed
content:
Before you review, open the PR and copy the exact latest commit hash. Enter it in the HAI field **R1 Reviewed PR Commit Hash** (its instruction: *"Please specify the exact commit hash (latest) that you will review"*), and review that commit. This matters because the PR can get new commits later: the second reviewer (R2) reads your recorded hash, confirms they're reviewing the same commit (it may not be the latest), and evaluates your review against the exact commit you saw. If your hash is wrong or missing, your review can't be fairly checked.
\`\`\`

### 8.2 Standard Quality Score – Review 1

Rate the quality of the task as you received it, 1–5 (see [Scoring](/reviewing/scoring) for the full scale and how each score maps to a verdict). Don't rely on a shorthand here: the line between a 2 and a Reject depends on whether the task's difficulty survives the fix, not on the number alone.

### 8.3 Review 1 Task Verdict

This verdict sets the routing. Choose one:

- ✅ **Accept**: this task is good to approve as is
- 🔄 **Revise**: this task is salvageable with revisions I have explained
- ❌ **Reject**: this task is unsalvageable

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Don't click Approve on a Revise or Reject
content:
Clicking **Approve** in HAI routes the task forward to the next review layer; it is not a neutral "submit review" button. Only click it when your Task Verdict is **Accept**, and note the system only treats an Accept as valid when **zero issues** are flagged. For **Revise** or **Reject**: flag the issue(s), leave your feedback, and do **not** click Approve. Wait for the gray send-back option to become available and use it, which routes the task back to the fellow. This has gone wrong before: reviewers intending to revise clicked Approve, and their tasks advanced to the next review layer instead of returning to the attempter. See the [Decision rule](/reviewing/judgment#6-the-verdict-accept-revise-reject) above.
\`\`\`

### 8.4 Review 1 Fellow Verdict

Separate from the task verdict: here you are rating the **fellow**, not the task.

- ⭐ **Excellent**: this fellow is already of exceptional quality
- 🎓 **Trainable**: this fellow is good and can be trained to successfully contribute on this project
- 🛑 **Misaligned**: this fellow is misaligned with the project guidelines or is not qualified

### 8.5 Task Notes and Feedback

- Only accept tasks that are deliverable. An Accept is only valid when there are **zero issues** flagged. Whenever you Revise or Reject, the task is sent back, so flag every issue as **general feedback**. Do **not** assign the minor or major issue categories separately.
- Leave feedback in **both** places: the taxonomy comment field **and** the inline text-bubble comment on the file, so the fellow sees it in their sidebar. A practical pattern: write one paragraph listing all issues, then file each issue as its own feedback bubble.
- Always provide feedback, including on a Reject. A rejection with no explanation feels terrible and teaches nothing; even an unsalvageable task is a chance to keep the fellow from repeating the mistake. Good feedback points at the exact file / criterion / line, names what is wrong, and says what to change, so the next revision has a high chance of approval.
- A rejected task is removed from the pipeline and will not be paid, so give solid reasoning for a Reject.
- If the fellow already received feedback from a previous review, first confirm they implemented the required changes.

Use the **R1 Other comments** field for any notes that aren't feedback to the fellow.

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: Review with the war room open
content:
The war room is a Zoom office hour where you can get help with any reviewer question. It's announced on Slack and reviewers are sent the invite. When it's active, keep it open while you review and ask questions in real time; unblocking a judgment call live beats guessing.
\`\`\`

**Related:** [Reviewer guide](/reviewing) · [Judgment areas, valid failures, and the verdict](/reviewing/judgment) · [Scoring](/reviewing/scoring)
`,C3=`---
title: Scoring — checkboxes and the 1–5 score
---

## 7. Scoring: checkboxes and the 1–5 score

You record a review in several parts: the **issue checkboxes**, a **comment**, a **1–5 Standard Quality Score**, and (in Review 1) a **Task Verdict** and **Fellow Verdict**.

### What each checkbox means

Select every issue that applies. Map your findings from [The judgment areas](/reviewing/judgment#4-the-judgment-areas) and [Valid vs. invalid failures](/reviewing/judgment#5-the-core-skill-valid-vs-invalid-failures) onto these options.

| **Checkbox** | **Select it when…** |
|----|----|
| **Instructions are overspecified** | The prompt hands over the method, mandates a tool/library, or walks through steps, so the task is no longer hard. |
| **Instructions are underspecified** | A sound expert approach would fail verification, an arbitrary choice the agent must match isn't disclosed, or the solution needs knowledge the agent was never given. |
| **Verifiers too tight. Low tolerances fail the tasks unfairly** | A genuinely correct solution from a different sound method falls outside the accepted band. |
| **Verifiers too loose. Wrong answers pass through** | A wrong or wrong-but-close answer passes, or there's a bypass / domain-specific cheat path the verifier misses. |
| **Task is not realistic issue** | A gimmick, trick, or toy puzzle; outputs no real practitioner would want. |
| **Instruction contain incorrect or irrelevant info** | Wrong paths, contradictions, claims that don't match the repo, or misleading filler. |
| **Metadata labels missing, placeholder, or wrong fit** | \`task_objective\` or \`artifact_type\` is unset, still a scaffold placeholder, drawn from outside the controlled vocabulary in \`.dynamo/diversity-taxonomy.toml\` (browseable on [Task categories](/task-categories)), or not the best-fit label for what the task actually does. (\`category\` / \`subcategory\` are seeded by the Dynamo team in the platform task; flag here when the fellow changed them or the task the PR implements no longer matches them.) |
| **This task is good. Send it forward** | All gates clear. Select only when you'd ship it as-is. |
| **Other (add comments)** | Anything not named above: too easy, not novel, hardcoded solution, tests not aligned to the instruction. Explain in the comment. |

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Comments must be actionable
content:
Point at the exact file, criterion, or line and say what to change. For example, "the [29,31] band rejects a valid trapezoidal-rule result; widen to [28,32] or justify the method restriction," not "verifier seems off." A specific comment is what lets the author fix it in one pass.
\`\`\`

### Standard Quality Score (1–5)

Score and verdict are set independently. The **verdict** answers whether the task can be salvaged (Accept / Revise / Reject); the **score** answers how good the task was on arrival (1–5). They don't move together: a task can be salvageable and still low quality. Sending a task back to Revise and grading it a 2 is a normal, intended outcome — it means "worth fixing, but the quality on arrival was poor," which is exactly the signal that lets us judge attempter quality over time. Only a **1** is inherently unsalvageable, because a 1 is reserved for bad faith (ignored feedback, spam), not merely poor work.

Score the task on arrival, meaning its quality before any suggested fixes. The score tracks your verdict, so don't agonize over 4-vs-5.

| **Score** | **Meaning** | **Verdict** |
|----|----|----|
| **5** | No issues | Accept |
| **4** | Minor, non-blocking issue (typos, grammar, or one very minor requirement of many left untested), still sendable to the client | Accept |
| **3** | A blocking-but-fixable issue that doesn't collapse the task's difficulty (ambiguity, incorrect facts, leaked solution fragments, missing required files such as \`test.sh\`), **or** no issues at all except that the task belongs to a different \`category\` than the platform records | Revise (or Accept, if \`category\` mismatch is the only issue) |
| **2** | Major issue and poor quality on arrival, independent of whether it's fixable. A fixable 2 is a normal Revise (send it back, low score recorded); a 2 whose fix would flip the difficulty, or that needs a rebuild, is a Reject | Revise or Reject |
| **1** | Attempter ignored or disputed valid reviewer feedback without addressing it, or the task is egregious spam / highly misaligned | Reject |

Quick reference table for scoring:

| **Case** | **Verdict** | **Score** |
|----|----|----|
| No issues | ✅ **Accept** | 5 |
| Minor issues that do not block delivery or flip the difficulty | ✅ **Accept** | 4 |
| No issues, but the task belongs to a different \`category\` | ✅ **Accept** | 3 |
| Minor issues that block delivery but do not flip the difficulty | 🔄 **Revise** | 3 |
| Major issues that block delivery but do not flip the difficulty | 🔄 **Revise** | 2 |
| Any issues that would flip the difficulty or require a fresh start | ❌ **Reject** | 2 |
| Ignoring valid feedback from previous reviewers | ❌ **Reject** | 1 |
| Egregious LLM/Spam | ❌ **Reject** | 1 |

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Calibrate before you score
content:
Set the score and the verdict independently: the **score** records the task's quality on arrival, the **verdict** records where it should go. Score 5 or 4 is clean enough to Accept. Score 3 is a minor blocking issue (Revise), with one special case: if the *only* issue is that the task belongs to a different \`category\` than the platform records, the task itself is deliverable, so Accept it and use the 3 to log the mismatch. Score a major issue a 2 for the quality read even when it's fixable. The Revise-vs-Reject call is then separate and rides on one question: does the task stay genuinely hard once fixed? If yes, Revise (a 2 sent back). If fixing it would flip the difficulty so the agents pass, or the task needs a full rebuild, Reject. Score 1 is reserved for bad faith: the attempter ignored valid feedback or the task is spam/misaligned.

Worked example: a task with a major design flaw that a competent fellow could still fix scores a 2 (poor quality) and gets a Revise (salvageable) — the low score records the quality problem for attempter tracking even though the task is going back rather than being rejected.
\`\`\`

**Related:** [Reviewer guide](/reviewing) · [Judgment areas, valid failures, and the verdict](/reviewing/judgment) · [Recording your review in HAI](/reviewing/recording)
`,S3=`---
title: Reviewer guide
---

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Project Dynamo — reviewer guide
content:
This section is for **reviewers** on Project Dynamo. Every submitted task is reviewed twice on the platform before it moves to Pending Pass@ — Review 1 makes the call, Review 2 is a second pass over that call. Your job as a reviewer is to reach the correct verdict (**Accept, Revise, or Reject**) on each submission and leave feedback the attempter can act on.
\`\`\`

## Overview

You review a real Terminal-Bench task a fellow built and decide whether it can go forward. Reviews are entirely **reading and judgment** — the automated layers already built the image, ran the oracle, and executed pass@5. You are the layer that catches the things a machine can't reliably judge: coherence across files, genuine difficulty, realism, ambiguity, verifier robustness, and whether the task is solvable as packaged.

For the full walkthrough — what the machine already did, how to prep for a review, the judgment areas, scoring, and how to record your verdict in HAI — see [Reviewer guidelines](/reviewing/guidelines).

Reviewers are paid at an hourly rate across every tier of the ladder below.

## Reviewer flow

Reviewers move through a promotion ladder based on how closely their calls align with high-quality R2 reviewers.

\`\`\`step-sequence
orientation: vertical
<1>
title: Onboarding Reviewer
content: When you're first promoted into reviewing, you start as an Onboarding Reviewer. Your reviews are graded and compared against the R2 review on the same task to measure alignment.
</1>
<2>
title: Unthrottled Reviewer
content: Consistent, high alignment with R2 on your reviews promotes you to Unthrottled Reviewer. A portion of your tasks will still be routed through the R2 layer so we can keep tracking the quality of your reviews.
</2>
<3>
title: R2 Reviewer
content: Exceptional review performance and very high alignment with the high-quality specialists already in R2 can lead to promotion into R2 itself — the final review layer on the platform.
</3>
\`\`\`

**Related:** [Reviewer guidelines](/reviewing/guidelines) · [The judgment areas](/reviewing/judgment) · [Scoring: checkboxes and the 1–5 score](/reviewing/scoring) · [Recording your review in HAI](/reviewing/recording)
`,_3=`---
title: Roles & progression
---

Everyone starts as an Attempter writing tasks. Consistently strong work can promote you up a reviewer ladder; a drop in quality can move you back down. Here's how the roles fit together. (Pay, work limits, and internal ops aren't covered here.)

Here's the progression — from where everyone starts, up to the top of the ladder:

\`\`\`step-sequence
orientation: vertical
<1>
title: Attempter — Attempt
content: You author tasks. Quality tiers within this role: Under Review → Attempter → Unthrottled Attempter. If your quality drops, you move down to Under Review Attempter.
</1>
<2>
title: R1 Reviewer — Review 1
content: First review of submitted tasks, in two tiers (Onboarding R1 → Unthrottled R1). Consistently strong, R2-aligned reviewing promotes you up. An Onboarding R1 reviewer whose quality slips can move back down to an Attempter role.
</2>
<3>
title: R2 Reviewer — Review 2
content: Final review of tasks that R1 accepted — the top of the ladder.
</3>
\`\`\`

How a reviewer routes a task — accept, send back for revision, or reject to Holding-Rejection — is shown on the [task pipeline](/).
`,dk=`---
title: Content ontology
---

Citadel reasons about two bodies of knowledge. One is the template's own know-how - its components, rules, and editorial moves - which is always active. The other is the **content ontology**: the blessed, reusable descriptions of the things trainings actually teach. It is drawn on automatically while you author, so every training describes a common concept the same way instead of reinventing it.

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: You don't edit this while authoring
content:
The content ontology is drawn on for you. Changing it is a separate maintenance mode, not part of normal training work.
\`\`\`

## What it gives you

A single agreed description of the concepts that recur across trainings - rubrics, criteria and their weights, what makes a check verifiable, edge cases, hallucination, and the like - together with the tasking best practices and quality criteria that go with them. When you author a page about one of these, the agent pulls the blessed description rather than improvising a new one. Quality is framed the way Handshake actually works - approval on review and reference examples - rather than abstract agreement statistics.

## How it layers

The same concept can be described once in general and then specialized for a kind of work. When you author, the layers that apply compose into one description, with each part's source tracked.

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: A general definition
content: Each common concept has one blessed, plain description that holds everywhere.
</1>
<2>
title: A task-type refinement
content: A kind of work - rubric scoring, quality review, preference ranking, prompt authoring, video segmentation, agentic evaluation - can add detail specific to it.
tip: Where projects genuinely disagree, the description names the variation instead of pretending there is one rule.
</2>
<3>
title: Composed for your page
content: When you edit a page, the applicable layers merge into a single description you can author from - consistent across trainings, with its sources visible.
</3>
\`\`\`

## The building blocks: four kinds of atom

Everything in the ontology is built from one of four kinds of unit - an "atom." Each answers a different question, so when you capture a piece of knowledge the first move is always to ask which question it answers.

\`\`\`accordion
<1>
title: Entity - what a term means and how to spot it
content: A term plus a test for recognizing it. Take Rubric: a plain description of what a rubric is, plus an operational test - could a second reviewer reach the same verdict working only from it? Entities are special. They own a concept's identity, so every other kind of atom ultimately points back at one.
</1>
<2>
title: Signal - how quality is measured
content: A criterion and how it is judged. Review approval, for instance - whether finished work passes review on the first or second pass, with clear lines for what counts as a pass, a borderline, or a fail. A signal always names the thing it measures.
</2>
<3>
title: Lever - the always or never move that improves the work
content: A craft technique you apply while working. "Grade substance, not style" is a move you make while judging an output. Because a lever teaches a skill, it spells out how to apply it and the anti-patterns that trip people up.
</3>
<4>
title: Policy - the standing rule, or the answer people keep asking for
content: A rule plus its rationale, or a question paired with its answer. "Can I use an LLM to do the work?" is a process-and-permission rule, not a craft skill. Policies cover what is required or allowed; levers cover how to do the work well.
</4>
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: Lever or policy? The line that is easy to miss
content:
Both sound like rules, so they are easy to confuse. The test: a lever teaches a skill you apply to produce better work, so it always has a "how to apply." A policy is a rule you comply with - about process, permission, or what makes a submission complete. "Cite the specific moment that decided your vote" is a lever. "Every submission must have all its tags filled in" is a policy.
\`\`\`

\`\`\`grouping-drill
context: Six rules pulled from real trainings. Three teach a craft move you apply while working; three are standing rules you simply comply with.
instruction: Sort each rule into Lever or Policy, then reveal to check your reasoning.
keyLesson: If it teaches a technique you apply to do better work, it is a lever. If it is a rule you comply with - about completeness, process, or permission - it is a policy.
<1>
kind: item
id: i1
text: Cite the specific moment that decided your judgment.
group: lever
</1>
<2>
kind: item
id: i2
text: Decide the winner first, then size how strongly you prefer it.
group: lever
</2>
<3>
kind: item
id: i3
text: When an answer contains an "and," split it into two.
group: lever
</3>
<4>
kind: item
id: i4
text: Every submission must have all its required tags filled in.
group: policy
</4>
<5>
kind: item
id: i5
text: Every frame in a segmentation timeline must belong to a labeled segment.
group: policy
</5>
<6>
kind: item
id: i6
text: Work must be claimed and time-tracked before you start, or it is not credited.
group: policy
</6>
<7>
kind: bucket
id: lever
label: Lever
modelAnswer: Each teaches a skill you apply while judging or authoring, with a technique to follow and anti-patterns to avoid.
</7>
<8>
kind: bucket
id: policy
label: Policy
modelAnswer: Each is a rule you comply with - about completeness or process - stated as a rule and its rationale, not a craft technique.
</8>
\`\`\`

## A worked example: one concept, three layers

A single concept is described once in general, then sharpened wherever a kind of work needs it. There are three ways a layer can touch the base description - it can add to it, sharpen it, or replace part of it.

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: The general definition
content: Rubric gets one plain description that holds everywhere - an ordered list of objective, verifiable criteria. This is the base every other layer builds on.
</1>
<2>
title: A refinement for a kind of work
content: Rubric scoring adds detail that only applies there - each criterion is scored independently, and a usable rubric balances required behaviors against named failure modes. A refinement can sharpen the general meaning for that context, or replace a specific part where the context genuinely differs.
tip: When two unrelated kinds of work both try to replace the same part, the system refuses to guess - it flags the clash for a human to settle.
</2>
<3>
title: A cross-cutting note
content: A theme like bias can annotate the same concept from the side - check that no criterion rewards a style tied to identity. It adds a reminder without changing the core meaning.
</3>
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: What you actually author from
content:
Open a page about rubric scoring and those three layers compose into one description - with each line tagged by where it came from, so you can always tell the general rule from the task-specific refinement from the cross-cutting note.
\`\`\`

## The frontmatter that wires it together

Every atom opens with a short block of structured fields. Most are housekeeping - a display **label**, a one-line **summary**, a **status** (draft, blessed, or deprecated; only blessed atoms are pulled into authoring), and a **version** that bumps when the meaning changes. Two fields do the real connective work.

\`\`\`accordion
<1>
title: aliases - the words people actually say
content: The synonyms for a concept, lowercased. A rubric might also be a "grading rubric" or a "scoring guide." This is how a loose request - "fix the grading guide" - resolves to the one right concept instead of spawning a duplicate. Good aliases are a big part of why the ontology stays deduplicated.
</1>
<2>
title: relations - the typed links between atoms
content: The connections between atoms, declared as data rather than buried in prose. A lever governs the concepts it applies to; a signal is measured by a metric; an entity can be part of a larger one, or confusable with a near neighbor worth contrasting. The build walks these links and fails if any target does not exist, so the graph never quietly rots.
</2>
\`\`\`

Relations are drawn from a **closed vocabulary** - you pick from a fixed set (governs, part-of, measured-by, confusable-with, and a handful more), never free text. Entities that refine a concept also carry an **about** field naming the concept they describe, and a **layer** that says whether they add, sharpen, or replace.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Where the exact syntax lives
content:
This page is the map, not the legend. The precise ids, the full relation list, and the field-by-field contract live in the schema that maintenance mode reads when you actually edit an atom - ask for it when you get there.
\`\`\`

## What never leaks

Two protections are built in and checked automatically on every change.

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Two firewalls
content:
The ontology is never shown to a learner reading a finished training. And one client's private vocabulary never reaches another client's training - names and project details stay with the project that owns them.
\`\`\`

## Updating it

When a genuinely reusable concept emerges - or an existing description should improve - it is captured through a dedicated maintenance mode rather than edited inline. That mode looks for an existing home before creating anything, can learn reusable concepts from an existing training, take a description from a document or a conversation, and draw the current structure so you can see how it fits together.

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: How to start
content:
Ask to enter ontology-update mode. It is the only way the content ontology changes, and it keeps both firewalls intact.
\`\`\`
`,A3=`---
title: Shared blocks
---

Shared blocks let Citadel apps reuse standard markdown-backed pages across multiple learning apps. The goal is simple: one published app owns the source page, and other apps can place that page in their own navigation without copying markdown.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Live reuse, not copy-paste
content:
The producer controls the page content and order inside the block. The consumer controls where that block appears in its own navigation.
\`\`\`

## Why shared blocks exist

Copying the same instructional page into several apps creates drift. One app gets a correction, another keeps the old version, and editors lose track of which version is authoritative. Shared blocks keep the source page in one app and let consumers render the live exported version.

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: Portable by design
content:
Shared pages must stay markdown-only, authorized by the publishing service, and rendered through the standard Citadel content system. That constraint keeps the same page safe in every consuming app.
\`\`\`

## How the skill works

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: Export a portable page
content: The exporting app declares \`sharedBlocks\` in \`src/content/manifest.md\`. The export can include one page or a parent page with its children, as long as every selected page is standard markdown content, not marked draft, and carries the right manifest taxonomy \`{type}\` tag for its sidebar icon. Portable page frontmatter includes \`title\` and optional \`subtitle\`; consumers render the subtitle under the page title when present.
</1>
<2>
title: Build a private artifact
content: \`renderBlocks.ts\` validates the declaration, parses the selected markdown with the shared parser, strips project-specific custom-token blocks with a warning, records local asset metadata, and writes private shared-block JSON under \`dist/.private/shared-blocks/\`.
</2>
<3>
title: Consume by placeholder
content: The consuming app adds a top-level manifest placeholder such as \`{{SHARED producer.learn.joinhandshake.com:blockName}}\`. In local and preview builds, Citadel renders deterministic placeholder pages. In production, the app waits for the service-authorized fetch, then uses the producer page's exported taxonomy type as the icon fallback if the producer label does not match a native consumer icon label.
</3>
<4>
title: Fail safely
content: Required placeholders fail closed if the block cannot load. Optional placeholders use a trailing \`?\` and can be omitted without blocking the rest of the app.
</4>
\`\`\`

## What the skill protects

\`\`\`accordion
<1>
title: Portability
content:
Shared pages cannot depend on custom React components, custom routes, project-specific hooks, resource entries, form configuration, or inline JSX. They must render through the standard markdown parser and \`ContentBlockRenderer\`.
</1>
<2>
title: Authorization
content:
Referencing one block from a producer domain authorizes the consuming app to consume every block exported by that producer domain until the consumer redeploys without that domain. The browser does not prove authorization; \`learn-apps\` reads private deployed metadata.
</2>
<3>
title: Asset safety
content:
Local assets are not embedded in the consuming app. They are recorded with byte size and SHA-256 metadata, then served through a same-origin proxy after authorization and integrity checks.
</3>
<4>
title: Runtime stability
content:
Consumers re-validate producer artifacts before merging shared pages into navigation. Custom-token blocks are removed with a warning because they depend on producer-specific component code; unknown content block types, unsafe strings, oversized artifacts, and route collisions are rejected instead of rendered partially.
</4>
\`\`\`

## When to use it

Use shared blocks when the same Citadel-authored instructional page should appear in several apps and remain live-linked to one source.

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Do not export custom app behavior
content:
Do not use shared blocks for project-specific pages, custom interactive experiences, draft content, or pages that need local app code.
\`\`\`

For the full operator workflow, see \`skills/shared-blocks.md\`. For the architecture decision, see \`docs/adr/2026-05-12-shared-blocks.md\`.
`,hk=`---
title: Skills and agents
---

Skills are markdown files in the \`skills/\` directory that teach agents how to perform specific tasks. Each skill defines rules, formats, and constraints for a domain - styling, writing, scaffolding, quality assurance. Agents load them automatically based on the task at hand.

## How skills load

Skills load in priority order. Earlier skills override later ones when rules conflict. The style skill is always active.

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: Style loads first
content: The style skill (\`skills/style.md\`) is always active. It defines colors, typography, spacing, and layout rules that no other skill can override.
tip: If an agent rejects your styling request, it is probably enforcing a style rule.
</1>
<2>
title: Task-specific skills activate
content: When you ask an agent to write content, it loads voice and pedagogy skills. When you scaffold, it loads the scaffold skill and starts Guided Scaffold by default. When you finish a task, it loads the QA check skill.
</2>
<3>
title: QA validates everything
content: Before completing any task, the agent runs the full QA checklist (\`skills/qa-check.md\`). Violations must be fixed before the task is considered done.
</3>
\`\`\`

## The skill catalog

\`\`\`accordion
<1>
title: Style (skills/style.md) - Priority 1
content:
The design system source of truth. Defines semantic color tokens, typography scale (Noi Grotesk for body, Sans Plomb for display, IBM Plex Mono for code), spacing rules, page layout (704px container, 640px content), heading hierarchy (h1 and h2 only), and component specifications.

**Always active.** Every styling decision must reference this skill.
</1>
<2>
title: Voice (skills/voice.md) - Priority 2
content:
Writing rules that sit between pedagogy philosophy and visual style. Defines two voice modes (conceptual for "why" content, procedural for "how" content), AI anti-patterns to avoid (filler phrases, hedging, structural uniformity), progressive depth (orient → explain → apply), clarity standards, and inclusivity requirements.

**Active when writing content of any kind.**
</2>
<3>
title: Pedagogy (skills/pedagogy.md) - Priority 3
content:
Educational principles that keep content grounded. Problem-posing (frame as problems, not facts), praxis (never separate understanding from doing), critical consciousness (name assumptions), humanization (respect reader intelligence), and visual engagement (every page needs interactive components).

**Active when writing text content.**
</3>
<4>
title: Scaffold (skills/scaffold.md)
content:
Generates a new project from external markdown. Guided Scaffold is the default: before writing files, the agent clarifies the learner, outcome, training mode, source-fidelity boundary, and possible enhancements. Then it parses sections, auto-detects components, generates content files, updates the manifest, and runs post-scaffold analysis.

**Auto-activates** when a source document is provided, when a user remixes from Citadel, or when the user asks to scaffold, sync, or migrate content. In a Citadel remix, scaffold intake is the first operator-facing step before customization, styling, feature work, or content edits. Can also be invoked explicitly with \`/scaffold\`. If you need the old mechanical path, ask for fast scaffold or use \`/scaffold --fast\`.
</4>
<5>
title: QA Check (skills/qa-check.md)
content:
Pre-completion validation checklist covering color system, typography, content management, component standards, spacing, table formatting, sidebar nesting, table integrity, dry-run cleanup, interactive content coverage, rhythmic variety, changelog integrity, asset size limits, scaffold health report, template integrity, security, milestone integrity, project name uniqueness, and cross-reference integrity - plus pedagogical analysis and a decision-oriented three-persona review for post-scaffold evaluation.

**Active before completing any task. Mandatory - not optional.**
</5>
<6>
title: Content Density (skills/content-density.md)
content:
Rules for preventing text walls. 300+ consecutive words without a component must be broken up. Pages target 600–1200 words. No 3+ consecutive paragraphs without a visual break. Codifies the anti-wall pedagogy principle.

**Active when managing text-heavy content.**
</6>
<7>
title: Component Skills
content:
Individual skill files for specific components: \`two-up.md\`, \`callout.md\`, \`accordion.md\`, \`example-pair.md\`, \`code-block.md\`, \`checklist.md\`, \`highlight.md\`. Each defines when to use the component, formatting rules, and detection patterns for scaffolding.

**Active when using the specific component.**
</7>
<8>
title: Component Development (skills/component-development.md)
content:
A template-maintenance workflow for creating reusable Citadel components and their attendant skills. It guides the agent through branch safety, overlap analysis, pedagogical justification, fenced-block schema design, parser and generator contracts, scaffold recognition, design-system requirements, and QA.

Use this for reusable Citadel infrastructure only. If a component is specific to one training app, use \`skills/custom-component.md\` instead. See [Component development](/content/component-development) for the fellow-facing guide.
</8>
<9>
title: Milestone (skills/milestone.md)
content:
Tracks fellow interactions. Two types: \`pageview\` (fires when a page loads) and \`click\` (fires on user action). Uses \`useMilestonePageView()\` hook and \`trackClick()\` function.

**Active when adding tracking to pages.**
</9>
<10>
title: Resource (skills/resource.md)
content:
External data fetching system. Register resources in a manifest, create mock JSON for local development, use the \`useResource\` hook in components. Production fetches from a configured API URL.

**Active when adding external data to an app.**
</10>
<11>
title: Shared Blocks (skills/shared-blocks.md)
content:
A template-maintenance workflow for exporting standard markdown-backed pages from one Citadel app and consuming them in another. It covers portable page validation, \`sharedBlocks\` manifest declarations, \`{{SHARED domain:block}}\` placeholders, private artifact generation, domain-scoped authorization, and safe failure behavior.

Use this when one Citadel-authored page should remain live-linked across multiple apps. See [Shared blocks](/rules/shared-blocks) for the dedicated guide.
</11>
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: The QA check is not optional
content:
Every task - scaffolding, editing, adding pages - must end with a full QA check. The checklist catches hardcoded colors, text walls, missing components, spacing violations, and content quality issues. Run it before every deployment.
\`\`\`

## Using skills effectively

Most skills load automatically - you never invoke them directly. When an agent refuses a request or asks a clarifying question, it is usually enforcing a skill rule. Knowing the skill catalog helps you understand and work with that behavior.

One skill requires explicit invocation: the QA check, which you request when you want a full pre-deployment review. The scaffold skill runs automatically when you hand the agent a source document - you don't need to type \`/scaffold\`. Guided Scaffold is the ordinary path; the fast scaffold escape hatch is available when you explicitly need mechanical conversion.
`,fk=`---
title: Template Development
---

Template development is the maintenance mode for improving Citadel itself. Use it when a fork or branch has evolved a better reusable design-system pattern, component behavior, skill workflow, scaffold rule, QA check, or supporting script that should move back into the base template.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Why this mode exists
content:
Citadel's normal guardrails protect apps from accidental template edits. Template development makes the opposite intent explicit: improve the reusable template on purpose.
\`\`\`

Ordinary Citadel work protects the template: content goes in markdown, routes stay simple, and core components remain stable. Template development deliberately changes that operating mode. The agent may edit normally protected files, but only to improve the reusable base system.

\`\`\`callout
variant: important
title: This is not app-building mode
content:
Use template development only when the goal is to improve base Citadel. If the goal is to build a single training app, stay in ordinary scaffold, sync, custom-component, or content-editing mode.
\`\`\`

## What the skill does

The \`iterate-template\` skill creates a controlled lifecycle for template-maintenance work. It records the current Git SHA as the baseline, starts a dedicated iteration branch in local development, guides systemic design decisions, and can generate a migration plan for applying the branch back to base Citadel.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Baseline first
content:
The baseline SHA is the anchor for every later plan. Template changes usually touch tokens, components, documentation, tests, and changelog entries together; the baseline lets the plan compare that full branch diff instead of summarizing from memory.
\`\`\`

## When to use it

Use template development when the operator asks to improve Citadel's reusable infrastructure rather than a single app.

\`\`\`checklist
<1>
id: port-fork-pattern
label: Port a successful fork pattern back to base Citadel
</1>
<2>
id: refine-design-system
label: Refine the design system, global CSS, or Tailwind token mapping
</2>
<3>
id: update-shared-components
label: Update reusable components or shared navigation chrome
</3>
<4>
id: change-infrastructure
label: Change scaffold, parser, generator, QA, or eval behavior
</4>
<5>
id: write-parity-plan
label: Write a parity plan for another branch or fork
</5>
<6>
id: add-first-class-component
label: Add a first-class reusable component workflow
</6>
\`\`\`

Do not use it for one-off course content, project-specific branding, or custom components that belong only to one app.

## Lifecycle

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: Enter mode
content: Run \`npm run iterate-template:init -- --intent "Short description"\`. In local development, this records the current SHA and cuts an \`iterate-template/...\` branch before protected template files are edited. In Lovable, use \`--no-branch\` if branch creation is unavailable.
</1>
<2>
title: Frame the system change
content: Write a short brief naming the intended template-level improvement, affected surfaces, design-system principle, unchanged areas, and QA needed. This keeps the work holistic instead of becoming a pile of spot fixes.
</2>
<3>
title: Implement across source-of-truth files
content: Make the reusable change and update the files that consume the same rule. For example, a component authoring change may require the skill, parser, generator, renderer, tests, and documentation to move together.
</3>
<4>
title: Validate the template
content: Run checks that match the touched surfaces, such as build, content QA, route checks, component-authoring drift checks, private-source checks, workflow evals, and targeted tests.
</4>
<5>
title: Generate the migration plan
content: Run \`npm run iterate-template:plan -- --name "Plan name"\`. The generated plan compares the iteration branch to the recorded baseline, lists changed files, inventories assets, and gives base Citadel a porting map.
</5>
\`\`\`

## Local branch behavior

When you enter template development locally, the helper script creates a branch from the current SHA. This is intentional. It leaves \`main\` as the clean base target and lets the migration plan describe how to apply the branch's work back to base Citadel.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Main stays the target
content:
Local branch creation keeps the base branch available as the thing the final plan updates, rather than mixing template experiments directly into main.
\`\`\`

If a branch already exists, the skill records it. If the working tree is dirty, the agent should ask whether to commit, stash, discard, or intentionally include the work after the baseline.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Why branch first
content:
The branch makes the iteration easy to compare against base Citadel. The plan can point from main to the branch instead of reconstructing changes from memory.
\`\`\`

## What remains protected

Template development relaxes the core-file editing restriction, but it does not remove safety rules.

\`\`\`checklist
<1>
id: asset-limit
label: Keep every added asset under 5MB
</1>
<2>
id: private-source-protection
label: Keep private source material and dogfood fixtures out of app output
</2>
<3>
id: source-of-truth-discipline
label: Update source-of-truth consumers when a canonical rule changes
</3>
<4>
id: qa-reporting
label: Run and report QA before completion
</4>
<5>
id: component-development
label: Use the component-development skill for new reusable interactive components
</5>
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: Think in systems
content:
A good template iteration does not just say, "change this class." It explains the reusable pattern: which token, component, skill rule, or QA behavior should exist so future Citadel apps inherit the improvement consistently.
\`\`\`

## Plan files

The migration plan is the handoff artifact. It should explain intent before mechanics, list every changed file, call out new or changed assets, name deleted files, document QA, and identify risks or follow-up decisions.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Plans carry assets too
content:
Plan files are generated under \`docs/plans/template-iteration/\`. Binary assets referenced by the plan are copied into an adjacent assets folder so the porting branch can carry the full change, not just prose instructions.
\`\`\`
`,pk='---\ntitle: Design tokens\n---\n\nCitadel\'s design system is built on semantic tokens - CSS variables that map to specific purposes rather than raw color values. This page documents the key tokens for colors, typography, spacing, and borders. When you need a color or size, reference a token - never hardcode a value.\n\n## Colors\n\nEvery color in a Citadel app comes from a semantic variable defined in `src/styles/colors.css`. These tokens automatically adapt between light and dark themes.\n\n```example-pair\ngood: className="text-foreground bg-background border-[var(--fg-border)]"\nbad: className="text-[#121212] bg-[#fcfcfd]" style={{borderColor: \'rgba(31,32,44,0.2)\'}}\ncontext: Semantic tokens adapt to the current theme. Hardcoded values break in dark mode, resist future changes, and violate the QA checklist. The QA check runs `grep` for hardcoded hex and rgb values.\n```\n\n```accordion\n<1>\ntitle: Background tokens\ncontent:\n| Token | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `--bg-surface` | Page surface, main background |\n| `--bg-primary` | Cards, elevated surfaces |\n| `--bg-secondary` | Secondary backgrounds |\n| `--bg-tertiary` | Tertiary backgrounds |\n| `--bg-disabled` | Disabled elements |\n| `--bg-inverted` | Inverted backgrounds |\n\nUse via Tailwind: `bg-background`, `bg-card`, `bg-secondary`, etc.\n</1>\n<2>\ntitle: Foreground tokens\ncontent:\n| Token | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `--fg-primary` | Primary text, headings |\n| `--fg-secondary` | Secondary text, descriptions |\n| `--fg-tertiary` | Muted content |\n| `--fg-border` | Borders, dividers |\n| `--fg-border-light` | Subtle borders |\n| `--fg-disabled` | Disabled text |\n| `--fg-inverted` | Inverted text |\n\nUse via Tailwind: `text-foreground`, `text-muted-foreground`, `border-[var(--fg-border)]`, etc.\n</2>\n<3>\ntitle: Interactive tokens\ncontent:\n| Token | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `--interactive-primary` | Primary buttons, key actions |\n| `--interactive-secondary` | Secondary accents |\n| `--interactive-hover` | Hover state backgrounds |\n| `--interactive-active` | Active/pressed states |\n| `--interactive-warning` | Warning actions |\n| `--interactive-info` | Info actions, links |\n| `--interactive-positive` | Success states |\n| `--interactive-negative` | Error states |\n\nThese map to Tailwind classes like `bg-primary`, `text-destructive`, etc.\n</3>\n<4>\ntitle: Status tokens\ncontent:\n| Token | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `--status-positive` | Success states (40% opacity) |\n| `--status-warning` | Warning states (40% opacity) |\n| `--status-negative` | Error states (40% opacity) |\n| `--status-info` | Info states (40% opacity) |\n| `--status-neutral` | Neutral states |\n\nAll status tokens use 40% opacity per the Figma spec.\n</4>\n```\n\n## Typography\n\nThree font families, each with a specific role. Never mix them.\n\n| Font | Use | Tailwind |\n|------|-----|----------|\n| **Noi Grotesk** | Body text, headings | `font-sans` (default) |\n| **Sans Plomb** | Large display text only | `font-accent` |\n| **IBM Plex Mono** | Code snippets | `font-mono` |\n\n```callout\nvariant: warning\ntitle: Never use Sans Plomb for page headings\ncontent:\nSans Plomb is reserved for large display text in hero sections. All page headings (h1, h2) use Noi Grotesk. Using `font-accent` on headings is a QA violation.\n```\n\n```accordion\n<1>\ntitle: Body text scale\ncontent:\n| Size | Pixels | Line height | Use |\n|------|--------|-------------|-----|\n| `text-body-sm` | 13px | 15.6px | Small labels |\n| `text-body-md` | 15px | 18px | **Default body text** |\n| `text-body-lg` | 17px | 23.8px | Large body text |\n| `text-body-xl` | 19px | 22.8px | Extra large body |\n</1>\n<2>\ntitle: Header text scale\ncontent:\n| Size | Pixels | Line height | Use |\n|------|--------|-------------|-----|\n| `text-header-sm` | 24px | 28.8px | Small headers |\n| `text-header-md` | 28px | 33.6px | Medium headers |\n| `text-header-lg` | 32px | 38.4px | **Page title (h1)** |\n| `text-header-xl` | 44px | 44px | Display text |\n</2>\n```\n\n## Spacing\n\nSpacing follows a 4px base unit. The key rule: **32px (`mt-8`) only between h2 sections - never elsewhere.**\n\n| Context | Value | Class |\n|---------|-------|-------|\n| Between components/paragraphs | 16px | `gap-4` |\n| Between h2 sections | 32px | `mt-8` |\n| Below h1 title | 10px | `mb-[10px]` |\n| Below h2 to paragraph | 4px | `mb-1` |\n| Page top padding | 52px | `pt-[52px]` |\n| Page side/bottom padding | 32px | `px-8 pb-8` |\n\n```callout\nvariant: tip\ntitle: The page container pattern\ncontent:\nEvery page uses the same container: `max-w-[704px] px-8 pb-8 pt-[52px]`. This gives 640px of content width with 32px padding on each side. The 52px top padding aligns the first baseline with the sidebar content.\n```\n\n## Borders\n\nBorders use the `--fg-border` token: `rgba(31, 32, 44, 0.2)` in light mode. Apply with `border-[var(--fg-border)]`.\n\nFor subtle borders (cards, inputs), use `--fg-border-light`. The default border radius is `0.5rem` (8px).\n',mk=`---
title: Voice and pedagogy
---

Citadel enforces two sets of writing rules: a **voice** guide that controls how content sounds, and a **pedagogy** framework that controls how content teaches. This page demonstrates both - every principle described here is applied to the page you are reading.

## Two modes of voice

All content operates in two modes, mixed freely within a page. Recognizing which mode you are in prevents the most common writing mistake: explaining *why* something matters using step-by-step language, or giving instructions using reflective language.

\`\`\`example-pair
good: Open **Settings > Configuration**. Select your timezone from the dropdown. Click **Save**.
bad: We might consider navigating to the Settings area, where one could potentially explore the various configuration options that are available to us.
context: The good version uses procedural voice - direct, second-person, action-oriented. The bad version uses conceptual voice for procedural content, producing vague, hedged instructions that waste the reader's time.
\`\`\`

**Conceptual mode** is for introductions, context, comprehension checks, and reflection. It poses questions, invites thinking, and frames *why* something matters. Markers: "we," "consider," "what might happen if."

**Procedural mode** is for step-by-step instructions, interface descriptions, and outcomes. It is direct, precise, and second-person. Markers: "Click," "Select," "Open," "you."

\`\`\`highlight
Pages naturally transition: {(1) conceptual intro} → {(2) procedural steps} → {(3) conceptual reflection}. If you are explaining *why* → conceptual. If you are describing *what to do* → procedural.

marginalia:
1: Dialogical, questioning, framing the purpose
2: Directive, specific, action-oriented
3: Returns to conceptual mode - now with the procedural steps as context, prompting the reader to evaluate what they just did
\`\`\`

## ^AI^ voice anti-patterns

Three categories of markers to identify and eliminate from your content.

\`\`\`accordion
<1>
title: Filler phrases (never use)
content:
These phrases add no information and signal AI-generated content:

- "Let's dive in" / "Let's explore"
- "It's important to note that"
- "In this section, we will"
- "As we've seen" / "As mentioned earlier"
- "Without further ado"
- "In today's world" / "In the modern landscape"

Delete every one. If the sentence still makes sense without the phrase, the phrase was filler.
</1>
<2>
title: Structural uniformity (vary deliberately)
content:
AI-generated content tends toward rigid parallelism. Fight it:

- Do not open every section the same way
- Vary paragraph length - some long, some single-sentence
- Surprise the reader with a short, blunt sentence after a complex one
- Do not make every list perfectly parallel

Variety signals a human voice. Uniformity signals a template.
</2>
<3>
title: Hedging (commit to a position)
content:
Replace vague qualifiers with direct statements:

| Hedged | Direct |
|--------|--------|
| "It might be helpful to consider" | "Consider" |
| "One could argue that" | State the argument |
| "It's generally recommended" | "Do X" or explain *why* |
| "You may want to think about" | "Think about" |
</3>
\`\`\`

## The pedagogy principles

Four principles keep content grounded, honest, and respectful. They are guardrails, not philosophy - they prevent the most common ways educational content fails.

\`\`\`step-sequence
<1>
title: Problem-posing
content: Frame situations as problems to solve, not facts to memorize. Give enough context that when readers hit trouble, they can improvise - not just follow steps.
tip: Pose genuine questions at transition points: "Why does the timing matter?" not "Note that timing is important."
</1>
<2>
title: Praxis
content: Never separate understanding from doing. Abstract concepts need concrete grounding. Instructions need enough context that the reader knows *why*, not just *what*.
</2>
<3>
title: Critical consciousness
content: Name your assumptions. Acknowledge when a recommendation has trade-offs. Do not present one approach as inevitable when alternatives exist.
</3>
<4>
title: Visual engagement
content: Walls of text reproduce passive learning. Every page must have at least one interactive component. No more than three consecutive paragraphs without a visual or interactive break.
tip: Components are not decoration - they must serve a pedagogical purpose.
</4>
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: tip
title: The read-aloud test
content:
Read your content aloud. If it sounds like an AI wrote it - smooth, uniform, hedged - rewrite. Good educational content has the texture of a knowledgeable person talking, not a language model generating.
\`\`\`

## Inclusivity

Three dimensions, all required in every piece of content.

**No assumed life experience.** Do not use examples that depend on specific hobbies, family structures, or cultural practices. Use universally accessible scenarios.

**No assumed technical level.** Explain terms the first time they appear. Do not say "as you know" or "obviously."

**Identity-neutral language.** Vary names across demographics. Avoid gendered language where irrelevant. No idioms that do not translate ("knock it out of the park," "the whole nine yards").
`,gk=`---
title: The rule system
---

Citadel apps are built by AI agents - in Lovable and Claude Code - that follow a hierarchy of rules. These rules enforce the design system, writing voice, pedagogical principles, and quality standards automatically. Understanding the rule system helps you work *with* the agents instead of fighting them.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: Rules are enforced, not suggested
content:
Both Claude Code and Lovable agents load these rules automatically from \`skills/\` files in priority order. When you prompt an agent to do something that violates a rule, it will push back or ask for clarification. That is working as intended.
\`\`\`

## The three layers

Rules live in three places, loaded in this priority order:

1. **Skills** (\`skills/*.md\`) - Specific capabilities and guidelines: style, voice, pedagogy, scaffolding, QA. See [Skills and agents](/rules/skills).
2. **Agent configuration** (\`AGENTS.md\`, \`CLAUDE.md\`) - What agents are allowed to do, skill loading order, hard requirements.
3. **Knowledge base** (\`.lovable/knowledge.md\`) - Architecture documentation and common violation warnings for the Lovable agent.

The style skill always loads first and overrides everything else. When rules conflict, earlier priorities win.

Explore the sub-sections: [Skills](/rules/skills) explains the full skill catalog. [Voice](/rules/voice) demonstrates the writing rules. [Tokens](/rules/tokens) documents the design system values.
`,N3="---\ntitle: Install Harbor\n---\n\nHarbor builds and runs your task locally in Docker. Install it once as a global tool:\n\n```code-block\nlanguage: bash\ncontent:\nuv tool install harbor\nharbor --version\n```\n\n```callout\nvariant: important\ntitle: ⚠️ Install `harbor`, not `harbor-cli`\ncontent:\nThe package you need is `harbor` — not `harbor-cli`. Both are technically CLIs, but `harbor-cli` is a completely different application and will not work for Dynamo tasks. Double-check the name before installing.\n```\n\n\nYou point Harbor at your task by running it from the `task/` directory (`harbor run -p . --agent oracle`) and it builds the single task image, runs it, and writes the reward to `/logs/verifier/`. (You do not need to clone terminal-bench-2 — your task lives in your own forked repo.)\n",I3=`---
title: Prerequisites
---

A one-time setup. Install all three before installing Harbor.

- **Docker** - Harbor uses Docker to build and run your task locally. See the install steps below.
- **uv** - Astral's Python package manager. \`curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh\`, then \`uv --version\`. See <https://astral.sh/uv>.
- **Python 3.11+** - \`python3 --version\`. \`uv\` will manage Python toolchains if you need a newer interpreter.

## Install Docker

Pick the install path for your OS, start Docker, and confirm it's running.

**macOS** - download Docker Desktop from <https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/> (choose the Apple Silicon or Intel build to match your machine), open the \`.dmg\`, and drag Docker to Applications. Launch Docker Desktop once so it finishes setup.

**Windows** - download Docker Desktop from <https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/> and run the installer. It will enable WSL 2 if it isn't already; reboot when prompted, then launch Docker Desktop.

**Linux** - install Docker Engine using the official convenience script, then add your user to the \`docker\` group so you can run it without \`sudo\`:

\`\`\`code-block
language: bash
content:
curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com | sh
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
\`\`\`

Full per-distro instructions: <https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/>.

### Verify

\`\`\`code-block
language: bash
content:
docker --version
docker ps
\`\`\`

\`docker ps\` should print an empty table (no error). If you see "Cannot connect to the Docker daemon," start Docker Desktop (macOS/Windows) or \`sudo systemctl start docker\` (Linux) and try again.

\`\`\`callout
variant: note
title: No API key needed for local work
content:
You do not need a model API key to scaffold a task, run the oracle agent, or calibrate locally. API keys come in only when you run a real evaluation against a hosted model.
\`\`\`
`,R3=`---
title: Calibration loop
---

The harness is correct if and only if it **fails a wrong solution and passes the golden one**. You'll run this loop after writing the tests in Step 5, and again after building the Dockerfile in Step 6.

## Wrong solution must fail (reward < 1.0)

Replace \`solve.sh\` with something trivially wrong - an empty script, a stub that writes nothing. Run Harbor from the \`task/\` directory.

\`\`\`code-block
language: bash
content:
echo '#!/bin/bash' > solution/solve.sh
harbor run -p . --agent oracle
cat /logs/verifier/reward.txt
# expect: reward < 1.0
\`\`\`

## Golden solve.sh must pass (reward 1.0)

Restore the real solution and re-run.

\`\`\`code-block
language: bash
content:
git checkout solution/solve.sh
harbor run -p . --agent oracle
cat /logs/verifier/reward.txt
# expect: 1.0
\`\`\`

Treat **reward 1.0 for golden, reward < 1.0 for stub** as the bar for moving to the next step. If \`harbor run -p . --agent nop\` passes, the verifier is too weak and is scoring a pass without the work being done - tighten the assertions until doing nothing fails.
`,P3=`---
title: Harbor commands
---

Run these from the **root of your task repo**.

| Command | What it does |
| --- | --- |
| \`harbor run -p . --agent oracle\` | Build the images and run the **oracle agent** (your \`solution/solve.sh\`) against the verifier. Expect **reward 1.0**. |
| \`harbor run -p . --agent nop\` | Run the **nop agent** (does nothing). It must **fail** — expect **reward < 1.0**. If it passes, your verifier is too weak. |

The loop you repeat: edit task files, then \`harbor run -p . --agent oracle\`. Oracle must score 1.0 and nop must score < 1.0 before you open a PR.

\`\`\`callout
variant: info
title: You don't need to run these yet
content: These commands come up later, during the workflow steps — after you've authored \`solve.sh\`, written tests, and built the Dockerfile. They're listed here so you know what Harbor will ask of you, not as something to run right now.
\`\`\`
`,O3=`---
title: Getting started
---

Three things before you build: install the prerequisites, install Harbor, and fork your assigned task repo.

## Prerequisites
- **Docker** installed and running
- **uv** installed — <https://astral.sh/uv>
- **Python 3.11+**
- **GitHub CLI** (\`gh\`) — <https://cli.github.com/>, then \`gh auth login\`

## Install Harbor

\`\`\`code-block
language: bash
content:
uv tool install harbor
harbor --version
\`\`\`

## Fork your task repo

You were assigned a task repo under \`handshake-project-dynamo\`. Fork it, clone your fork, and make a working branch. You don't have write access to the base — you propose changes via a pull request.

\`\`\`code-block
language: bash
content:
gh repo fork handshake-project-dynamo/<your-task-repo> --clone
cd <your-task-repo>/task
\`\`\`

## Core Harbor commands (run from the \`task/\` directory)

\`\`\`code-block
language: text
content:
harbor run -p . --agent oracle  →  run your solution against the verifier (expect reward 1.0)
harbor run -p . --agent nop     →  run the no-op agent; doing nothing must score reward < 1.0
\`\`\`

\`\`\`callout
variant: info
title: You don't need to run these yet
body: These commands come up later, during the workflow steps — after you've authored \`solve.sh\`, written tests, and built the Dockerfile. They're listed here so you know what Harbor will ask of you, not as something to run right now.
\`\`\`

No model API key is needed to scaffold, run the oracle, or calibrate locally.
`,bk=`---
title: Splash screen
---

The splash screen is a full-screen overlay that appears before a user enters the training app. It is designed for legal acknowledgement - terms of use, confidentiality notices, program conduct expectations - and requires the user to scroll through the content before continuing.

\`\`\`callout
variant: warning
title: Work in progress
content:
The splash screen component is available for preview and feedback but is not yet ready for production use. Configuration details may change before the stable release.
\`\`\`

## How it works

The splash screen is **one per project** - it is configured in the manifest, not on individual pages. When enabled, it appears on first load and (if the user does not check "Don't show again") on subsequent visits. Dismissal state is stored in \`localStorage\`, keyed to the authenticated user's profile ID so that each user's preference is tracked independently.

The user must scroll to the bottom of the legal text before the **Continue** button becomes active. This is intentional and cannot be disabled - it ensures the content has been presented in full.

## Setting it up

First, ensure \`app-config.json\` at the project root has a **unique \`projectName\`**. The storage key for localStorage is derived from this - not from the splash display name.

\`\`\`code-block
language: json
content:
{
  "projectName": "acme-training-module-1",
  "defaultProjectId": "proj-abc-123",
  "forms": {}
}
\`\`\`

Then add a \`splash:\` block to the YAML frontmatter in \`src/content/manifest.md\`:

\`\`\`code-block
language: yaml
content:
splash:
  enabled: true
  project_name: Acme Training
  tagline: Everything you need to get started.
  button_label: Continue
  background_color: "#1a1a2e"
  doodle_image: /assets/doodle.svg
\`\`\`

All fields except \`enabled\` are optional. See the table below for defaults.

## Configuration reference

| Field | Type | Default | Description |
|-------|------|---------|-------------|
| \`enabled\` | boolean | \`false\` | Set to \`true\` to activate the splash on load |
| \`project_name\` | string | - | Displayed above "Welcome" in small caps |
| \`tagline\` | string | - | One-line descriptor shown below "Welcome" |
| \`button_label\` | string | \`Continue\` | Label on the dismiss button |
| \`storage_key\` | - | Derived from \`app-config.projectName\` | Set \`projectName\` in \`app-config.json\`; do not configure here |
| \`background_color\` | string (hex) | - | Optional hex color; foreground text auto-adjusts for WCAG AA contrast |
| \`doodle_image\` | string (URL) | - | Optional decorative image, positioned bottom-right, aria-hidden |

## Authoring the legal text

The splash screen reads its body content from \`src/content/splash.md\`. Edit that file using standard markdown. All inline components (callouts, code blocks, etc.) are supported, though for legal text a clean prose structure is recommended.

The file ships with placeholder lorem ipsum text. Replace it with your project's actual terms before enabling the splash screen.

## Resetting for testing

The storage key is \`{projectName}-splash-dismissed\`. To clear it for all users on this browser:

\`\`\`code-block
language: javascript
content:
// Replace with your app-config.projectName + "-splash-dismissed"
Object.keys(localStorage)
  .filter(k => k.startsWith('acme-training-module-1-splash-dismissed'))
  .forEach(k => localStorage.removeItem(k));
\`\`\`

## Keyboard navigation

The splash screen fully supports keyboard operation:

- **Tab** cycles focus between the "Don't show again" checkbox and the Continue button
- **Shift+Tab** cycles in reverse
- **Space** toggles the checkbox when focused
- **Space / Enter** activates the Continue button when focused (only when scrolled to bottom)

Focus is trapped inside the overlay while it is open. The Escape key does not dismiss the splash - this is intentional for acknowledgement-gate semantics.
`,ig=`---
